#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "parametric masks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The parametric mask feature offers fine-grained selective control over how individual pixels are masked. It does this by automatically generating an intermediate blend mask from user-defined parameters. These parameters are color coordinates rather than the geometrical coordinates used in drawn masks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "For each data channel of a module (e.g. Lab, RGB) and several virtual data channels (e.g. hue, saturation) you  can construct a per-channel opacity function. Depending on each pixel's value for a given data channel this function calculates a blending factor between 0 and 1 (100%) for that pixel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each pixel of an image thus has different blending factors for each of its data channels. All blending factors are finally multiplied together (pixel-by-pixel), along with the value of the global opacity slider, to form a complete parametric blend mask for the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If the blend mask has a value of 0 for a given pixel, the input of the module is left unchanged. If the blend mask has a value of 1 (100%) for a pixel, the module has its full effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "channel tabs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on one of the channel tabs to select a data channel to use to build your mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Modules acting in (_display-referred_) _Lab_ color space have data channels for L, a, b, C (chroma of LCh) and h (hue of LCh). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Modules acting in _display-referred RGB_ color space have data channels for g (gray), R, G, B, H (hue of HSL), S (saturation of HSL), and L (lightness of HSL). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Modules acting in _scene-referred RGB_ color space have data channels for g (gray), R, G, B, Jz (luminance component of JzCzhz), Cz (chroma, or saturation, of JzCzhz), and hz (hue of JzCzhz). The g (gray) value is calculated as a weighted average of the R, G & B channels, the exact weightings depending on the working color space being used. The JzCzhz color space is a polar representation of the Jzazbz color space, in the same way that LCh is a polar representation of the Lab space. Like the L in Lab color space, the Jz is a representation of the luminosity of a pixel that aligns with how we perceive brightness. However, the Jzazbz color space is much better for high dynamic range images and is less susceptible to hue shifts than Lab space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_See [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_space) for more details about these color spaces._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Two sliders can be shown for each associated data channel: one that works on the _input data_ that the module receives and one that works on the _output data_ that the module produces prior to blending. The sliders for the output data channels are hidden by default and can be shown using the _show output channels_ option in the blending menu.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _boost factor_ slider allows the range of values targeted by the parametric mask sliders to be extended. It may be used in scene referred editing, where luminance values may extend beyond 100%, to target highlights. This slider is only available for channels where it is meaningful.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![input and output sliders](./parametric/input-output-sliders.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "inspecting data channels & masks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Press the letter C while hovering over a channel's input/output slider to view the input/output image data for that color channel. The center image changes to display that color channel either in gray-scale values or in false colors depending on the setting in [preferences > darkroom > display of individual color channels](../../../preferences-settings/darkroom.md). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Press the letter M to see the resulting mask for that slider overlaid on the image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When the mouse pointer leaves the slider the image returns to normal after a short delay. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "linear / log mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Press the letter A while hovering over the a slider to change its display to 'log' mode. This provides more fine control in the shadows. Press A again to toggle back to 'linear' mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "channel input/output sliders"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "With each color channel slider you can construct a trapezoidal opacity function. For this purpose there are four markers per slider. Two filled triangles above the slider mark the range of values where opacity is 1. Two open triangles below the slider mark the range values where opacity is 0. Intermediate points between full and zero are given a proportional opacity.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The filled triangles, or inside markers, indicate the closed (mostly narrower) edge of the trapezoidal function. The open triangles, or outside markers, indicate the open (mostly wider) edge of the trapezoidal function. The sequence of the markers always remains unchanged: they can touch one another but they cannot switch position.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A polarity (+/-) button to the right of each the slider switches between \"range select\" and \"range de-select\" modes, with visual confirmation provided by exchanging the upper and lower triangle markers. These two types of trapezoidal functions are represented graphically in the following images. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**range select**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![range select slider](./parametric/blendif_2a.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![range select graph](./parametric/blendif_2b.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**range deselect**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![range deselect slider](./parametric/blendif_3a.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![range deselect graph](./parametric/blendif_3b.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In their default state all markers are at their extreme positions. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In this state a range select function selects the whole range of values giving an “all at 100%” mask. Starting from there one can move the sliders inwards to gradually exclude more and more parts of the image except for the remaining narrow range.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Conversely a range de-select function (enabled by toggling the polarity) by default deselects the whole range of values, giving an “all-zero” mask as a starting point. Moving the sliders inwards gradually includes more and more parts of the image except for the remaining narrow range. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "color pickers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "With the left-hand color picker button you can select a point or area probe from your image. The corresponding values for the real and virtual data channels are then displayed within each color channel slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "With the right-hand color picker button you can automatically set the slider's values based on the selected range. Click and drag to set the parameters for the input slider from the drawn rectangle; Ctrl+click and drag to set the parameters for the output slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "invert"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the invert button above the sliders to invert the polarity of the entire parametric mask. This differs from the polarity buttons beside the individual sliders which just invert the parameters for the current slider/channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "reset"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the reset button above the sliders to revert all parametric mask parameters to their default state.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "drawn masks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "With the drawn mask feature you can construct a mask by drawing shapes directly onto the image canvas. Shapes can be used alone or in combination. Once a shape has been drawn on an image it can be adjusted, removed, or reused in other modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Shapes are stored internally as vectors and are rendered with the required resolution during pixelpipe processing. Shapes are expressed in the coordinate system of the original image and are transformed along with the rest of the image by any active distorting modules in the pipe ([_lens correction_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md), [_rotate and perspective_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-perspective.md) for example). This means that a shape will always work on the same image area regardless of any modifications that may be subsequently applied. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The controls required to create and alter drawn masks may be enabled by selecting either the \"drawn mask\" or \"drawn & parametric mask\" icon at the bottom of a module. You can also create and edit shapes using the [mask manager](../../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "creating shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Choose a shape by clicking on the appropriate shape icon (from left to right: circle, ellipse, path, brush, gradient).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![shape icons](./drawn/shape-icons.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This will take you into the creation mode for that shape. Once you have finished drawing your shape you will automatically be taken into edit mode. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+click on the shape icon to continuously draw multiple shapes of the same type -- each time a shape is completed, you will re-enter creation mode for a new instance of that shape. While in continuous creation mode, right-click on the image to stop drawing shapes and enter edit mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "For all drawn shapes, you can hold Shift while scrolling with the mouse wheel to change the extent of the shape's feathering (the blur at the edge of the shape) and use Ctrl+scroll to change the shape's opacity (how transparent it is). These operations are available in both creation and edit modes (as long as your mouse is over the shape in question).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default, scrolling your mouse up increases the value of the relevant shape parameters. This behavior can be changed in [preferences > darkroom > scroll down to increase mask parameters](../../../preferences-settings/darkroom.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** When used in shape creation mode, the preceding scroll operations will also cause the _default_ feathering or opacity to be changed. The new default values will be used the next time you create a new shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "editing shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the 'show and edit mask elements' icon ![show-and-edit-masks-icon](./drawn/shape-edit.png#icon) to enter shape edit mode. This will show all drawn masks in use by the current module and allow you to edit those shapes. It will also expand the associated group in the [mask manager](../../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md). Ctrl+click on the same icon to enter restricted edit mode, where certain actions (e.g. dragging a complete shape or changing its size) are blocked. This is particularly useful to avoid costly mistakes when editing path and brush shapes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click and drag a shape to move it around the image canvas. Clicking on a shape will also select that shape in the mask manager.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "removing shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "While in edit mode right-click on a shape to remove it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "reusing shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You can reuse shapes that you have drawn in other modules. Click on the shapes drop-down (next to the 'show and edit mask elements' button) to choose previously-drawn shapes individually or to use the same group of shapes as used by another module. The following options are available for selection:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"add existing shape\n"
": Choose either an individual shape or a group of shapes that you've drawn previously (either within the [mask manager](../../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md) or from within the drawn mask of another module). If that shape or group is used elsewhere, any changes you make will be reflected everywhere the shape or group is used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"use same shapes as\n"
": Add a list of shapes used in another module to the current module's mask. This differs from the previous option in that it creates a new group of shapes, allowing shapes to be added to or removed from the group independently of the module from which they were copied. All shapes that are common to both groups remain linked.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "combining and managing shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The [mask manager](../../../module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md) module can be used to manage your drawn shapes. This module also allows you to group and combine drawn masks using set operators (union, intersection, difference, exclusion).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "shape distortions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In order to ensure a consistent co-ordinate system, when you place a shape on the image, it is actually drawn on the original RAW file. This shape then passes up through the pixelpipe before finally being used by the module and drawn on the screen. This means that, if you have any enabled any distorting modules (such as lens correction), drawn shapes may appear distorted on the screen and in the final image. This can lead, for example, to circles being rendered as ellipses and gradient lines becoming curved. If you need to create a more accurate shape (to overcome these distortions) it is recommended that you avoid using the simple shapes (circles / ellipses) in favor of the path shape (which can be drawn using more points, reducing distortions). You can adjust the curve on gradient lines to overcome the simple distortions introduced by lens correction.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "available shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"circle\n"
": Click on the image canvas to place the circle. Scroll while hovering over the circle to change its diameter. Scroll while hovering over the circle's border to change the width of the feathering (the same effect as holding Shift while scrolling with the mouse wheel within the main shape).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ellipse\n"
": The general principle is the same as for the circle shape. In addition, four nodes are shown on the ellipse line. Click on the nodes to adjust the ellipse's eccentricity. Ctrl+click and drag the nodes or use Shift+Ctrl+scroll (with the mouse wheel) to rotate the ellipse. Shift+click within the shape to toggle the gradual decay between equidistant and proportional mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"path\n"
": Click on the image canvas to place three or more nodes and generate a free-format enclosed shape. Terminate the path by right-clicking after having set the last point. By default, nodes are connected with smooth lines. If you want a node to instead define a sharp corner, you can do so by creating it with Ctrl+click.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": In edit mode Ctrl+click on an existing node to convert it from smooth to sharp corners and vice versa. Ctrl+click on one of the line segments to insert an additional node. Right-click on a node to delete it. Take care to ensure that the mouse pointer is over the desired node and the node is highlighted, to avoid accidentally removing the whole path.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": The size of the completed shape can be modified by scrolling. The same holds true for the width of the border (the area with a gradual opacity decay), which can also be changed with Shift+scroll (with the mouse wheel) from anywhere within the shape. Single nodes as well as path segments can be moved by dragging them with the mouse. If a node is selected by clicking on it, a further control point appears which allows you to modify the curvature of the line (reset to default by right-clicking). Dragging one of the control points on the border adjusts the border width just in that part of the shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Consider fine-tuning paths in restricted edit mode (enabled by Ctrl+clicking on the 'show and edit mask elements' icon). This allows you to adjust single nodes and segments without the risk of accidentally shifting or resizing the whole shape. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"brush\n"
": Start drawing a brush stroke by left-clicking on the image canvas and moving the mouse while keeping the button pressed. The brush stroke is finalized once you release the mouse button. Scroll the mouse to change the shape size, either before you start drawing or at any time during the operation. Likewise you can use the \"`{`\" and \"`}`\" keys to decrease/increase feathering, and the \"`<`\" and \"`>`\" keys to decrease/increase opacity.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": If you have a graphics tablet with pen pressure sensitivity, darktable can apply the recorded pen pressure to certain attributes of the brush stroke. This operation can be controlled in [preferences > darkroom > pen pressure control for brush masks](../../../preferences-settings/darkroom.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": On lifting the tablet pen or releasing the left mouse button the brush stroke is converted into a number of connected nodes, which define the final shape. A configuration option ([preferences > darkroom > smoothing of brush strokes](../../../preferences-settings/darkroom.md)) controls how much smoothing is applied. A higher level of smoothing leads to fewer nodes being created – this eases subsequent editing at the expense of lower accuracy.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Nodes and segments of a brush stroke can be modified individually. See the documentation on path shapes (above) for more details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Rendering a complex brush shape can consume a significant number of CPU cycles. Consider using the circle, ellipse or path shapes instead where possible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"gradient\n"
": The gradient shape is a linear gradient which extends from a given point to the edge of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Click on the image canvas to define the position of the line that defines 50% opacity. Dotted lines indicate the distance beyond which the opacity is 100% and 0%. Between these dotted lines the opacity changes linearly. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": The line has two anchor nodes which you can drag to change the rotation of the gradient. You can also set the rotation angle when placing the gradient shape by clicking and dragging to place the shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Gradient lines can also be curved by scrolling with your mouse while hovering close to the center line. This can be useful to counteract the distortion caused by the [_lens correction_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md) module. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Depending on the module and the underlying image, using a gradient shape might provoke banding artifacts. You should consider activating the [_dithering_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md) module to alleviate this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "reversing the polarity of a drawn mask "
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the \"`+/-`\" button to reverse the polarity of the entire drawn mask. For example, a circular mask will, by default, cause the module to be applied only to the area inside the drawn circle. Reversing its polarity will cause the module to apply to the whole image, _except for_ that circle.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "masking & blending"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "blend modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Blend modes define how the input and output of a module are combined (blended) together before the module's final output is passed to the next module in the pixelpipe. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Classic blending modes, designed for display-referred RGB (constrained to 0-100%), implicitly define a fulcrum at 50% (gray) or 100% (white) in their algorithms, depending on the blend mode. Because scene-referred is not subject to these restrictions, this fulcrum needs to be explicitly defined by the user when performing blending operations in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space. The additional _blend fulcrum_ parameter will be presented to the user when using one of these blend modes in this color space. The effect depends on the operator used. For example, values above the fulcrum might be brightened and values below darkened, or vice versa.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The final output of a module is computed 'per-pixel' as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "final_output = (1.0 - opacity) * module_input + opacity * blended_output\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "where the `blended_output` is a combination of the input and output images, depending on the blend mode (below), and the `opacity` is defined 'per-pixel' by a combination of the mask and global opacity parameter. An opacity of 0% outputs an image that is identical to the input image of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The \"reverse\" button ![blend-reverse](./blend-modes/blend-reverse.png#icon) effectively reverses the roles of the input and output images in the 'per-pixel' computation:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "final_output = (1.0 - opacity) * module_output + opacity * blended_input\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "where the `blended_input` is a combination of the output and input images, depending on the blend mode below where _output_ and _input_ image references are reversed. In \"reversed\" blend modes, an opacity of 0% outputs an image that is identical to the _output_ image of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "normal modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normal\n"
": The most commonly used blend mode, \"normal\" simply mixes input and output to an extent determined by the opacity parameter. This mode is commonly used to reduce the strength of a module's effect by reducing the opacity. This is also usually the blend mode of choice when applying a module's effect selectively with masks. This mode is also known as the \"over\" Porter-Duff alpha blending operator (see [alpha compositing](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_compositing) for more details).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normal bounded\n"
": _not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space_\n"
": This blend mode is the same as “normal”, except that the input and output data are clamped to a particular min/max value range. Out-of-range values are effectively blocked and are not passed to subsequent modules. Sometimes this helps to prevent artifacts. However, in most cases (e.g. highly color-saturated extreme highlights) it is better to let unbound values travel through the pixelpipe to be properly handled later. The “normal” blend mode is therefore usually preferred.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "arithmetic modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"addition\n"
": Add together the pixel values of the input and output images, lightening the output. When blending in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space, the pixel values of the output image are multiplied by a value proportional to the \"blend fulcrum\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"subtract\n"
": Subtract the pixel value of the _output_ from the _input_. When blending in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space, the pixel values of the output image are multiplied by a value proportional to the \"blend fulcrum\". Pixel values less than 0 are set to 0.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"multiply\n"
": Multiply the pixel values of the input and output together. When blending in display-referred color spaces, pixel values are between 0 and 1.0, the final output will be clamped and will always be darker. When blending in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space, this value is further multiplied by a value proportional to the \"blend fulcrum\". In this case, values may be greater than 1.0 and therefore brighten the base image. This may have other side-effects, such as updating the white point in the filmic module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Multiply blending simulates an optical variable density filter, where the density is defined by the output of the module. It has many applications, from blooming and local contrast enhancements (when used with a blur or low-pass filter) to dodging/burning and global contrast enhancements (when used with exposure). The fulcrum sets the output intensity threshold between darkening and brightening (any RGB value below fulcrum will darken).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"divide\n"
": Divide the pixel values of the input by the output. When blending in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space, the pixel values of the output image are multiplied by a value proportional to the \"blend fulcrum\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Since this is the inverse of the multiply mode, it will darken where multiply brightens and vice versa. Everything else works in essentially the same way.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"screen\n"
": _not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space_\n"
": Invert the input and output pixel values, multiply those values together and invert the result. This yields approximately the opposite effect to \"multiply\" mode -- the resulting image is usually brighter, and sometimes “washed out” in appearance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"average\n"
": Return the arithmetic mean of the input and output pixel values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"difference\n"
": Return the absolute difference between the input and output pixel values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"geometric mean\n"
": Return the square root of the product of the input and output pixel values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"harmonic mean\n"
": Return the product of the input and output pixel values, multiplied by 2 and divided by their sum.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "contrast enhancing modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following modes are not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" blending color space as they rely on an assumption of \"50% mid gray\" which only applies to display-referred and non-linear color spaces.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"overlay\n"
": This mode combines the \"multiply\" and \"screen\" blend modes: The parts of the input where the output is brighter, become brighter; The parts of the image where the output is darker, become darker; Mid-gray is unaffected. This mode is often combined with the [_lowpass_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/lowpass.md) and [_highpass_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/highpass.md) modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"softlight\n"
": This mode is similar to \"overlay\", except the results are softer and less bright. As with overlay, it is often combined with the [_lowpass_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/lowpass.md) and [_highpass_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/highpass.md) modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hardlight\n"
": This mode is not related to \"softlight\" in anything but name. Like overlay mode it is a combination of \"multiply\" and \"screen\" modes and has a different effect above and below mid-gray. The results with hardlight blend mode tend to be quite intense and usually need to be combined with a reduced opacity.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"vividlight\n"
": This mode is an extreme version of overlay/softlight. Values darker than mid-gray are darkened; Values brighter than mid-gray are brightened. You will probably need to tone down its effect by reducing the opacity\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linearlight\n"
": This mode is similar to the effect of \"vividlight\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pinlight\n"
": This mode performs a darken and lighten blending simultaneously, removing mid-tones. It can result in artifacts such as patches and blotches.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "color channel modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Lab channels"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following are available for blending in the Lab color space only\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Lab lightness\n"
": Mix the lightness from the input and output images, while taking the color channels (a and b) unaltered from the input image. In contrast to “lightness” this blend mode does not involve any color space conversion and does not clamp any data. In some cases this blend mode is less prone to artifacts than “lightness”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Lab a-channel\n"
": Mix the Lab \"a\" color channel from the input and output images, while taking the other channels unaltered from the input image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Lab b-channel\n"
": Mix the Lab \"b\" color channel from the input and output images, while taking the other channels unaltered from the input image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Lab color\n"
": Mix the Lab color channels (a and b) from the input and output images, while taking the lightness unaltered from the input image. In contrast to “color” this blend mode does not involve any color space conversion and does not clamp any data. In some cases this blend mode is less prone to artifacts than “color”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "RGB channels"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following are available when blending in RGB color spaces only.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RGB red channel\n"
": Mix the \"red\" channel from the input and output images, while taking the other channels unaltered from the input image. When blending in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space, the \"red\" channel from the output image is multiplied by a value proportional to the \"blend fulcrum\". \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RGB green channel\n"
": Mix the \"green\" channel from the input and output images, while taking the other channels unaltered from the input image. When blending in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space, the \"green\" channel from the output image is multiplied by a value proportional to the \"blend fulcrum\". \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RGB blue channel\n"
": Mix the \"blue\" channel from the input and output images, while taking the other channels unaltered from the input image. When blending in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space, the \"blue\" channel from the output image is multiplied by a value proportional to the \"blend fulcrum\". \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "HSV channels"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following are available when blending in the \"RGB (display)\" color space only.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"HSV lightness\n"
": Mix the lightness from the input and output images, while taking color unaltered from the input image. In contrast to “lightness” this blend mode does not involve clamping.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"HSV color\n"
": Mix the color from the input and output images, while taking lightness unaltered from the input image. In contrast to “color” this blend mode does not involve clamping.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "others"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lightness\n"
": Mix lightness from the input and output images, while taking color (chroma and hue) unaltered from the input image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"chrominance\n"
": Mix chrominance from the input and output images, while taking lightness and hue unaltered from the input image. This blend mode uses RGB ratios, divided by a Euclidean norm.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lighten\n"
": _not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space_\n"
": Compare the pixel values of the input and output images, and output the lighter value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"darken\n"
": _not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space_\n"
": Compare the pixel values of the input and output images, and output the darker value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": _not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space_\n"
": Mix hue (color tint) from the input and output images, while taking lightness and chroma unaltered from the input image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color\n"
": _not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space_\n"
": Mix color (chroma and hue) from the input and output images while taking lightness unaltered from the input image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": _Caution: When modules drastically modify hue (e.g. when generating complementary colors) this blend mode can result in strong color noise._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"coloradjustment\n"
": _not available in the \"RGB (scene)\" color space_\n"
": Some modules act predominantly on the tonal values of an image but also perform some color saturation adjustments (e.g. the [_levels_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/levels.md) and [_tone curve_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/tone-curve.md) modules). This blend mode takes the lightness from the module's output and mixes colors from input and output, enabling control over the module's color adjustments.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each processing module takes its input from the preceding module in the pixelpipe, performs its operation on the image data, and then hands the output to the next module in the pixelpipe. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A module's output data can optionally be reprocessed (combined) with its input data before being handed to the next module. This additional processing step is called _blending_ -- input and output data is reprocessed using algorithms called blending operators or [blend modes](./blend-modes.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each blend mode is further controlled by the _opacity_ parameter (having a value between 0% and 100%) which defines how much the input and output images contribute to the final result. Typically an opacity of 0% outputs an image which is identical to the input image (the module has no effect) whereas an opacity of 100% delivers the maximum effect of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This opacity can be the same for every pixel (using the global opacity slider), in which case blending acts uniformly over the entire image. Alternatively the opacity values can vary depending on the properties or location of each pixel. This local modification of opacity is called a _mask_. Masks provide the user with fine control over which parts of an image are affected by a module and to what extent. The user may choose to activate a [drawn mask](./masks/drawn.md), a [parametric mask](./masks/parametric.md) or a [combination](./masks/drawn-and-parametric.md). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Blending and masking functionality is controlled via a group of icons located at the bottom of each applicable module. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![mask & blend options](./overview/mask-blend-options.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These icons enable the following masking and blending options, from left to right:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"off\n"
": Module output is passed to the next module in the pixelpipe without additional reprocessing. No further controls are displayed. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"uniformly\n"
": Input and output images are reprocessed uniformly with the chosen blend mode, where the amount of blending is controlled by a single opacity slider. Additional controls are displayed to allow the blend mode and opacity to be selected. The default is a blend mode of “normal” with an opacity of 100%.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[drawn mask](./masks/drawn.md)\n"
": Reprocessing takes place with the chosen blend mode and an opacity based on pixel location as defined by one or more drawn shapes. Additional controls are displayed to allow mask elements to be drawn. If no mask elements are drawn then all pixels have the same opacity, as defined by the opacity slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[parametric mask](./masks/parametric.md)\n"
": Reprocessing takes place with the chosen blend mode and an opacity based on the properties of individual pixels. Additional controls are displayed to allow the opacity to be adjusted on a per-pixel basis, determined by pixel values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[drawn & parametric mask](./masks/drawn-and-parametric.md)\n"
": Reprocessing takes place with the chosen blend mode and an opacity based on a combination of a drawn and parametric mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[raster mask](./masks/raster.md)\n"
": Reprocessing takes place with the chosen blend mode and an opacity based on a mask that was generated by an active module earlier in the pixelpipe.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blending options\n"
": Choose which color space to use when calculating the blending mask, and specify whether or not to allow a mask to be generated based on the module's output channels (normally a parametric mask is generated based on the input channels coming into the module). The following options are available:\n"
": - _reset to default blend colorspace_: Use the default color space for the module to specify the parametric mask.\n"
": - _Lab_: Use the Lab color space (where available) to specify the parametric mask.\n"
": - _RGB (display)_: Use the display-referred RGB/HSL color space to specify the parametric mask.\n"
": - _RGB (scene)_: Use the scene-referred RGB/J<sub>z</sub>C<sub>z</sub>h<sub>z</sub> color space to specify the parametric mask.\n"
": - _show output channels_: Show the [parametric mask](./masks/parametric.md) output channel controls, so that the parametric mask can be defined in terms of the module's output channels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Not all of these blending options are available for every module.\n"
msgstr ""

