#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A simple yet powerful tool to manage color channels.  \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module accepts red, green and blue channels as an input and provides red, green, blue, gray, hue, saturation and lightness channels as output. It allows you to independently control how much each input channel contributes to each output channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "RGB matrix multiplication"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You can think of the _channel mixer_ as a type of matrix multiplication between a 3x3 matrix and the input [R G B] values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _red_ then set the Rr, Rg & Rb values using the red, green and blue sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _green_ then set the Gr, Gg & Gb values using the red, green and blue sliders \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set the destination to _blue_ then set the Br, Bg & Bb values using the red, green and blue sliders \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default, _channel mixer_ just copies the input [R G B] channels straight over to the matching output channels. This is equivalent to multiplying by the identity matrix:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As an example use case, the following matrix is useful for taming ugly out-of-gamut blue LED lights by making them more magenta:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌  1.00  -0.18  0.18 ┐ \n"
"│ -0.20   1.00  0.20 │\n"
"└  0.05  -0.05  1.00 ┘ \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In this case it is useful to use a [parameteric mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) to limit the effect of the _channel mixer_ to just the problematic colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A more intuitive take for what the _channel mixer_ sliders do:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _red_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more red. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more cyan.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _green_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more green. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more magenta.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _blue_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more blue. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more yellow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Another very useful application of the _channel mixer_ is the ability to mix the channels together to produce a grayscale output -- a monochrome image. Use the _gray_ destination, and set the red, green and blue sliders to control how much each channel contributes to the brightness of the output. This is equivalent to the following matrix multiplication:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When dealing with skin tones, the relative weights of the three channels will affect the level of detail in the image. Placing more weight on red (e.g. [0.9, 0.3, -0.3]) will make for smooth skin tones, whereas emphasising green (e.g. [0.4, 0.75, -0.15]) will bring out more detail. In both cases the blue channel is reduced to avoid emphasising unwanted skin texture.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Different types of traditional black and white film have differing sensitivities to red, green and blue colors, and this can be simulated by setting the gray destination coefficients appropriately. The _channel mixer_ module has a number of built-in presets that can be used to achieve this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"destination\n"
": Select the destination channel that will be affected by the slider settings immediately below. The red, green and blue destination channels are used for color mixing as described in the _matrix multiplication_ section above. The gray channel is used for making grayscale images as described in the _monochome_ section above. It is also possible to define the R, G & B input channels to produce HSL (hue, saturation and lightness) values on the output, although this is a very specialised application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"red\n"
": Defines how much the red input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"green\n"
": Defines how much the green input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blue\n"
": Defines how much the blue input channel should contribute to the selected destination channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "defringe (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.6 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_chromatic aberrations_](./chromatic-aberrations.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Remove color fringing, which often results from Longitudinal Chromatic Aberrations (LCA), also known as Axial Chromatic Aberrations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module uses edge-detection. Where pixels are detected as a fringe, the color is rebuilt from less saturated neighboring pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"operation mode\n"
": _global average_: This mode is is usually the fastest but might show slightly incorrect previews at high magnification. It might also protect the wrong regions of color too much or too little by comparison with local average.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": _local average_: This mode is slower because it computes local color references for every pixel. However it might protect color better than global average and allows for rebuilding color where actually required. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": _static threshold_: This mode does not use a color reference but directly uses the threshold as given by the user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"edge detection radius\n"
": The algorithm uses the difference between the input image and a gaussian-blurred version of the same image to detect edges. This parameter controls the spatial extent of the gaussian blur used in the edge detection. Try increasing this value if you want a stronger detection of the fringes or the thickness of the fringe edges is too high.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/defringe.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": The threshold over which the edge of a pixel is counted as a “fringe”. Try lowering this value if there is not enough fringe detected and increasing it if too many pixels are desaturated.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "fill light (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_tone equalizer_](./tone-equalizer.md) module or the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module with a [drawn mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md).**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Locally modify exposure based on pixel lightness.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module pushes exposure by increasing lightness with a Gaussian curve of a specified width, centered on a given lightness.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exposure\n"
": The fill-light exposure (EV)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"center\n"
": The median lightness impacted by the fill-light. The lightness must be set manually but a color picker can be used to provide a guide based on a sample from the image. The lightness of the selected point/area is displayed in the gradient bar.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/fill-light.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"width\n"
": The width of the Gaussian curve. This number is expressed in zones, with the full range being 10 zones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "framing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Generate a frame around the image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The frame consists of a border (with a user-defined color) and a frame line within that border (with a second user-defined color). Various options are available to control the geometry and color of the frame.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"border size\n"
": The size of the frame as a percentage of the underlying full image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"aspect\n"
": The aspect ratio of the final module output (i.e. the underlying image plus the frame)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"orientation\n"
": The orientation of the frame (portrait/landscape). Select 'auto' for darktable to choose the most reasonable orientation based on the underlying image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"horizontal/vertical position\n"
": Select from a set of pre-defined ratios to control where the underlying image will be positioned on the horizontal/vertical axis. You can also right click and enter your own ratio as \"x/y\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"frame line size\n"
": The percentage of the frame line size, relative to the border size at its smallest part.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"frame line offset\n"
": The position of the frame line, relative to the underlying image. Choose 0% for a frame line that touches the image. Choose 100% for a frame line that touches the outer border.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"border color / frame line color\n"
": A pair of color selectors which allow the border and frame line colors to be defined. Clicking on the colored field will open a color selector dialog which offers a choice of commonly-used colors, or allows you to define a color in RGB color space. You can also activate a color picker to take a color probe from the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/framing.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/crop-rotate.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show guides\n"
": Tick the box to show guide overlays whenever the module is activated. Click the icon on the right to control the properties of the guides. See [guides & overlays](../utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md) for details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "global tonemap (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_filmic rgb_](./filmic-rgb.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Compress the tonal range of an HDR image into the limited tonal range of a typical LDR output file. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Global tonemap processes each pixel of an HDR image, without taking the local surrounding into account. This is generally faster than local [_tone mapping (deprecated)_](./tone-mapping.md), but might lead to less convincing results with very high-dynamic-range scenes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"operator\n"
": The operator to use. _Reinhard_, _Filmic_ and _Drago_ global tonemap operators are available. Depending on the selected operator, different parameters can be adjusted. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Some operators are fully self-adjusting, and do not require specific controls.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"bias (_Drago_ operator only)\n"
": This parameter influences the contrast of the output image. It is an essential parameter for adjusting the compression of high values and the visibility of details in dark areas. A value of 0.85 is recommended as a starting point.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"target (_Drago_ operator only)\n"
": A scale factor to adjust the global image brightness to the brightness of the intended display. It is measured in cd/m, and should match the brightness of your output device. Higher values lead to a brighter image, while lower values lead to a darker image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/global-tonemap.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"detail (all operators)\n"
": This parameter controls how much detail is preserved from the original input image and transferred back into the output image after tonemapping.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "invert (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_negadoctor_](./negadoctor.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Invert scanned negatives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color of film material\n"
": Clicking on the colored field will open a color selector dialog which offers you a choice of commonly used colors, or allows you to define an RGB color. You can also activate the color picker to take a color probe from your image – preferably from the unexposed border of your negative.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lens correction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Automatically correct for (and simulate) lens distortion, transversal chromatic aberrations (TCA) and vignetting.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module identifies the camera/lens combination from the image's Exif data and uses the external [lensfun library](https://lensfun.github.io/) to provide correction parameters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If your system's lensfun library has no correction profile for the automatically identified camera/lens combination, the controls for the three photometric parameters (below) are replaced with a warning message. You may try to find the right profile yourself by searching for it in the menu. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If your lens is present in the list but has not been correctly identified, this may require some adjustment within the exiv2 program (see [this post](https://dev.exiv2.org/boards/3/topics/2854) for details). Note that you may need to re-import the images once such adjustments have been made as the lens name is retrieved as part of the import process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If you can't find your lens, check if it is in the list of [currently supported lenses](https://lensfun.github.io/lenslist/), and try running the [`lensfun-update-data`](https://lensfun.github.io/manual/v0.3.2/lensfun-update-data.html) tool. If there is still no matching profile for your lens, a [lens calibration service](https://www.darktable.org/2013/07/have-your-lens-calibrated/) is offered by Torsten Bronger, one of darktable's users. Alternatively you may visit the [lensfun project](https://lensfun.github.io/lenslist/) to learn how to generate your own set of correction parameters. Don't forget to share your profile with the lensfun team!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"camera\n"
": The camera make and model as determined by the image's Exif data. You can override this manually and select your camera from a hierarchical menu. Only lenses with correction profiles matching the selected camera will be shown.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lens\n"
": The lens make and model as determined by the image's Exif data. You can override this manually and select your lens from a hierarchical menu. This is mainly required for pure mechanical lenses, but may also be needed for off-brand / third party lenses. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"photometric parameters (focal length, aperture, focal distance)\n"
": Lens corrections depend on certain photometric parameters that are read from the image's Exif data: focal length (for distortion, TCA, vignetting), aperture (for TCA, vignetting) and focal distance (for vignetting). Many cameras do not record focal distance in their Exif data, in which case you will need to set this manually.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": You can manually override all automatically selected parameters. Either take one of the predefined values from the drop-down menu or, with the drop-down menu still open, just type in your own value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"corrections\n"
": Choose which corrections (distortion, TCA, vignetting) darktable should apply. Change this from its default \"all\", if your camera has already performed some internal corrections (e.g. vignetting), or if you plan to undertake some corrections with a separate program.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"geometry\n"
": In addition to correcting lens flaws, this module can change the projection type of your image. Set this combobox to the desired projection type (e.g. \"rectilinear\", \"fish-eye\", \"panoramic\", \"equirectangular\", \"orthographic\", \"stereographic\", \"equisolid angle\", \"thoby fish-eye\").  To correct the aspect ratio of an anamorphic lens, use the [_rotate and perspective_](./rotate-perspective.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scale\n"
": Adjust the scaling factor of your image to avoid black corners. Press the auto scale button (to the right of the slider) for darktable to automatically find the best fit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": The default behavior of this module is to _correct_ lens flaws. Switch this combobox to \"distort\" in order to instead _simulate_ the flaws/distortions of a specific lens (inverted effect).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"TCA overwrite\n"
": Check this box to override the automatic correction parameters for TCA. This will expose the TCA red and TCA blue parameters below. Un-check the box to revert back to automatic corrections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"TCA red; TCA blue\n"
": Override the correction parameters for TCA. You can also use these sliders to manually set the parameters if the lens profile does not include TCA correction. Look out for colored seams at features with high contrast edges and adjust the TCA parameters to minimize those seams.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"corrections done\n"
": Occasionally, for a given camera/lens combination, only some of the possible corrections are supported by lensfun's profiles. This message box will tell you which corrections have actually been applied to the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** TCA corrections will not be applied to images that have been identified as monochrome (see [developing monochrome images](../../guides-tutorials/monochrome.md) for more information).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lens-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** The lens correction module will fill in missing data at the borders by repeating the borders' pixels. For strong corrections, this filling can be visible (especially on noisy images). Crop the image if necessary.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "liquify"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Move pixels around by applying freestyle distortions to parts of the image using points, lines and curves.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each of liquify's tools is based on nodes. A point consists of a single node and a line or curve consists of a sequence of linked nodes defining a path.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each instance of the liquify module is limited to a maximum of 100 nodes -- for more nodes, use additional instances. However, please note that the liquify module consumes a lot of system resources. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Drag the central point of a node to move the node around. The radius describes the area of the effect (distortion occurs only within this radius). To change the radius drag the handle at the circumference. A strength vector starting from the center describes the direction of the distortion, and its strength is depicted by the length of the vector. Change the vector by dragging its arrow head. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "points"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A point consists of a single node and strength vector. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the point icon to activate the point tool and then click on the image to place it. Hold Ctrl while clicking on the point icon to add multiple points without having to click the icon again each time. Right-click to exit creation mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "point modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The strength vector of a point has three different modes. These can be toggled by holding Ctrl and clicking on the arrowhead of the strength vector.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linear\n"
": A linear distortion inside the circle, starting from the opposite side of the strength vector and following the vector's direction. This is the default mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![linear](./liquify/liquify_ex1.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radial growing\n"
": The strength vector's effect is radial, starting with a strength of 0% in the center and increasing away from the center. This mode is depicted by an additional circle with the arrow pointing outwards.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![radial growing](./liquify/liquify_ex4.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radial shrinking\n"
": The strength vector's effect is radial, starting with a strength of 100% in the center and decreasing away from the center. This mode is depicted by an additional circle with the arrow pointing inwards.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![radial shrinking](./liquify/liquify_ex3.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "feathering"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"default mode\n"
": By default the strength varies linearly from 0% to 100% between the center and the radius of the control point. It is possible to modify the feathering effect by clicking on the center of the circle.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![default](./liquify/liquify_ex1.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"feathered mode\n"
": In \"feathered\" mode, two control circles are displayed, which can be modified independently to feather the strength of the effect. Note that clicking the center of the circle again hides the feathering controls but does _not_ return to the default mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![feathered](./liquify/liquify_ex2.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "removing points"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A point can be removed by right-clicking on the center of the node.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "lines and curves"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Lines and curves are sequences of points linked together by straight or curved lines. The effect is interpolated by a set of associated strength vectors. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the appropriate icon to activate the line or curve tool and then click on the image to place a sequence of points forming the path. Right-click anywhere when the last point has been placed in order to finish drawing the line/curve.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Hold Ctrl while clicking on the line/curve icon to add multiple lines/curves without having to click the icon again each time. Right-click a second time to exit creation mode after the final line or curve has been completed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lines\n"
": ![lines](./liquify/liquify_ex5.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"curves\n"
": ![curves](./liquify/liquify_ex6.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+click on a line or curve segment to add a new control point. Ctrl+right-click on the center of a node to remove a control point. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on a segment to remove the shape completely. Ctrl+Alt+click on a segment to change that segment from a line to a curve and vice versa.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "link modes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+click on the center of a node to change the way the points of a curve are linked together. There are four modes, which correspond to different ways of handling the steepness of the bezier curve using control handles: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"autosmooth\n"
": This is the default mode, in which control handles are not displayed -- controls are automatically computed to give a smooth curve.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cusp\n"
": Control handles can be moved independently. This mode is depicted by a triangle symbol in the node's center.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"smooth\n"
": Control handles always give a smooth curve. This mode is depicted by a diamond symbol in the node's center.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"symmetrical\n"
": Control handles are always moved together. This mode is depicted by a square symbol in the node's center.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "view and edit nodes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the node tool icon to activate or deactivate the node edit tool. This displays all currently-defined distortion objects and their controls. Alternatively you can right-click on the image at any time for the same effect. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "warps and nodes count"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This information field displays the number of warps (individual distortion objects) and nodes currently in use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "show guides"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/liquify.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/crop.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Tick the box to show guide overlays whenever the module is activated. Click the icon on the right to control the properties of the guides. See [guides & overlays](../utility-modules/darkroom/guides-overlays.md) for details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "orientation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Rotate the image 90 degrees at a time or flip the image horizontally and/or vertically. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The module is enabled by default and the orientation (rotation) is automatically set based on the image's Exif data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The orientation can also be set using the [selected images](../utility-modules/lighttable/selected-image.md) module in the [lighttable](../../lighttable/_index.md) view.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"transform\n"
": Double click the label to reset to the default transformations\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![rotate counter-clockwise](./orientation/rotate-counter-clockwise.png#icon) rotate counter-clockwise\n"
": Rotate the image 90 degrees counter-clockwise\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![rotate clockwise](./orientation/rotate-clockwise.png#icon) rotate clockwise\n"
": Rotate the image 90 degrees clockwise\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![flip horizontally](./orientation/flip-horizontal.png#icon) flip horizontally\n"
": Flip the image (mirror) horizontally\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/orientation.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![flip vertically](./orientation/flip-vertical.png#icon) flip vertically\n"
": Flip the image (mirror) vertically\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "retouch"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Remove unwanted elements from your image by cloning, healing, blurring and filling using drawn shapes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module extends the capabilities of the deprecated [_spot removal_](./spot-removal.md) module (equivalent to this module's \"clone\" tool) by including a \"heal\" tool (based on the heal tool from GIMP), as well as \"fill\" and \"blur\" modes. It can also take advantage of [wavelet decomposition](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md), allowing the image to be separated into layers of varying detail (from coarse to fine) which can be selectively retouched before being recombined to produce the output image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "clone and heal"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Cloning allows a part of the image (the _target_) to be hidden by replacing it with an area copied from elsewhere in the image (the _source_). For example, you may wish to remove a small cloud from a blue sky:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-original](./retouch/rt-original.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The simplest way to do this is with the _cloning_ tool ![retouch-clone-icon](./retouch/rt-clone-icon.png#icon). The following example uses a circular shape to clone out the cloud using the circle of blue sky beside it:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-clone](./retouch/rt-clone.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In many cases, the edges of the _source_ shape won't precisely match the surroundings of the _target_, leading to unnatural looking results. In this example, the sample of sky we chose as the source was slightly darker than the target, leaving a faint outline of the circular shape used in the cloning process:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-clone-nocontrol](./retouch/rt-clone-nocontrol.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In such cases, the _heal_ tool ![retouch-heal-icon](./retouch/rt-heal-icon.png#icon) is more appropriate. With this tool, the color and luma of the sample is blended to fit better with the surroundings. In this example, using _heal_ instead of _clone_ produces a much more pleasing result:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-heal-nocontrol](./retouch/rt-heal-nocontrol.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "source and target shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have chosen _heal_ or _clone_ mode, you must choose the shape you wish to use (_circle_, _ellipse_, _path_ or _brush_ -- see the [drawn masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) section for details). The source and target patches will both use the same shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When you hover over the image with your mouse, a plus symbol (+) will appear to indicate where the _source_ shape will be placed by default. Your normal mouse cursor will indicate the position of the target shape:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-source-cross](./retouch/rt-source-cross.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "It is recommended that you choose the position of the source shape first, followed by the position of the target, as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Shift+click to set the position of the source shape in \"relative mode\". The position of the \"plus\" (+) symbol will move to the clicked location and will remain in a fixed position _relative to your cursor_ until you click on the image to begin placing your target shape. If you place subsequent shapes without first changing the target location, the source shape will be placed at the same offset from the target shape as was used for the first stroke.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+Shift+click to change the position of the source shape in \"absolute\" mode. As above, the position of the \"plus\" (+) symbol will move to the clicked location, but will _remain in the same absolute position_ even if you move your mouse. You can then click on the image to begin placing the target shape. If you place subsequent shapes without first changing the target location, exactly the same source position will be used, fixed in the absolute coordinate system of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have placed your source and target shapes on the image, they can be adjusted manually with your mouse.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** For _circle_ and _ellipse_ shapes only, you can place both the source and target shapes with a single click-and-drag motion: Click on the desired target location and then drag, releasing your mouse button when you reach the desired source location. This operation does not affect the placement of subsequent shapes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "fill and blur"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _clone_ and _heal_ tools both require the use of another part of the image to \"fill in\" the region being hidden. Sometimes there is no suitable sample in the image to use for this purpose. In such cases, the _retouch_ module offers two further options:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-fill-icon](./retouch/rt-fill-icon.png#icon) fill tool\n"
": Fill the drawn region with a selected color.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-blur-icon](./retouch/rt-blur-icon.png#icon) blur tool\n"
": Apply a blur to the drawn region, smoothing out any details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These two options are most useful when used together with wavelet decomposition, where they can be used to smooth over features within a selected detail layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Wavelets allow an image to be decomposed into a number of layers each containing varying levels of detail, so that you can work on each detail layer independently and then recombine them at the end. This is particularly useful in portrait photography, where you can deal with skin blotches and blemishes on a coarse layer of detail, leaving the finer skin texture untouched. The [_wavelets_](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md) section provides more information on the decomposition process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This method can be used with the healing tool, for example, to paint over a spot that appears in one of the coarse detail layers, while leaving the hairs in the fine detail layers intact:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-beard-preserve](./retouch/rt-beard-preserve.jpg#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "It can also be used with the blur tool to even out coarse blotches in the skin, again without impacting the finer details (see the [_wavelets_](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md) section for details on this technique).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-overview](./retouch/rt-overview.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "retouch tools"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _retouch tools_ section consists of two items:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shapes\n"
": The number after the _shapes_ label indicates how many shapes have been placed on the image, either directly or within a wavelet layer. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Click on one of the shape icons to draw a new shape on the image (see [drawn masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) for details). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Ctrl+click on a shape icon to draw multiple shapes continuously (right-click to cancel). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Click the _show and edit shapes_ ![retouch-shapes-icon](./retouch/rt-shapes-icon.png#icon) button to show and edit any existing shapes for the currently-selected wavelet scale.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"algorithms\n"
": Choose a retouching algorithm (clone, heal, fill or blur). Ctrl+click to change the algorithm used for the currently-selected shape. Shift+click to set the default algorithm (used for new images or when you reset module parameters).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "wavelet decompose"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _wavelet decompose_ section centres around a bar graph that shows how the image has been decomposed into detail (scale) layers. The key features of the bar graph are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The black square on the left represents the entire image before decomposition.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The gray squares show the various wavelet detail layers, with fine details to the left, and coarse details to the right.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The white square on the far right represents the residual image (the remainder of the image after the detail layers have been extracted).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A light gray dot in a square indicates the currently-selected layer. Click on another square to select a different layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The light gray bar running along the top indicates which levels of detail are visible at the current zoom level. Zoom in to see finer details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The triangle at the bottom shows how many layers the image has been decomposed into. Drag the triangle to the right to create more layers. Drag it to the left to decrease the number of layers. By default no wavelet decomposition is performed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The triangle at the top shows the current value of the \"merge from\" parameter (see below).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The orange lines under the squares indicate which layers have retouch edits applied.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The remaining items in this section are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scales\n"
": Shows how many detail layers the image has been decomposed into. Zero indicates that no wavelet decomposition has been performed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"current\n"
": Shows which layer is currently selected (also marked with the light gray dot on the bar graph).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"merge from\n"
": This setting allows a single edit to be applied to multiple consecutive scales within a group starting from the coarsest scale (excluding the residual image) down to the scale selected. For example, if \"merge from\" is set to 3 and the maximum scale is 5 then all edits that are added to scale 5 will be applied to scales 3, 4 and 5. Edits added to scale 4 will be applied to scales 3 and 4, and edits added to scale 3 will be applied to scale 3 only. If you set _merge from_ to 0, then merging is disabled, and all edits apply only to the scale that they are defined in. Setting _merge from_ to the highest scale available (in this example, 5) also disables merging.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"           merge_from\n"
"               v\n"
"   0   1   2   3   4   5    scale\n"
"               <-------o    scale 5 edits\n"
"               <---o        scale 4 edits\n"
"               o            scale 3 edits\n"
"           o                scale 2 edits\n"
"       o                    scale 1 edits\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-display-icon](./retouch/rt-display-icon.png#icon) display wavelet scale\n"
": Display the currently-selected wavelet layer on the center image. Selecting this option brings up an additional control -- _preview single scale_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"preview single scale\n"
": An additional control that allows the black, white and gray points of the wavelet scale preview to be adjusted to make it easier to see. Click the ![auto-levels-icon](./retouch/rt-auto-levels-icon.png#icon) to set these values automatically. This does not affect the module's operation -- only the wavelet scale preview.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-cut-icon](./retouch/rt-cut-icon.png#icon) cut\n"
": Cut all shapes from the currently-selected layer and place them into the clipboard.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-paste-icon](./retouch/rt-paste-icon.png#icon) paste\n"
": Move the shapes on the clipboard to the currently-selected layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-hide-icon](./retouch/rt-hide-icon.png#icon) temporarily switch off shapes\n"
": Toggle all shapes (whether on the current layer or not) on or off, temporarily removing the module's effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-mask-icon](./retouch/rt-mask-icon.png#icon) display masks\n"
": Show the target shapes associated with the currently-selected layer with a yellow overlay.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This section allows you to modify settings related to the currently-selected shape:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shape selected\n"
": Indicates which shape is currently selected, and what type of shape it is.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fill mode\n"
": If the _fill_ algorithm has been chosen for the currently-selected shape, choose whether to \"erase\" or fill the selected shape with a chosen \"color\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fill color\n"
": If a _fill mode_ of \"color\" has been chosen, select the color to fill the shape with. You can click to select or enter a custom rgb value or use the color picker to take a sample from the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"brightness\n"
": If the _fill_ algorithm has been chosen for the currently-selected shape, fine-tune the color's brightness. This slider also works in \"erase\" mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blur type\n"
": If the _blur_ algorithm has been chosen for the currently-selected shape, choose whether to apply a \"gaussian\" or \"bilateral\" blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blur radius\n"
": If the _blur_ algorithm has been chosen for the currently-selected shape, choose the radius of the blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mask opacity\n"
": Alter the opacity of the mask associated with the currently-selected shape. An opacity of 1.0 indicates that the shape is completely opaque and the module's effect is fully applied, whereas a value less than 1.0 indicates that the effect applied by the shape is blended with the underlying image to the degree indicated by the slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "spot removal (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.6 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the \"cloning\" tool in the [_retouch_](./retouch.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Correct areas of an image (the target) using details from another area of the image (the source).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module uses some of the shapes that are available for [drawn masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) (circles, ellipses and paths), and the user interface is similar. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To use this module, first select the desired shape by clicking the corresponding shape icon (Ctrl+click to enable continuous shape creation mode). Next, you may optionally choose the source for the correction by using Shift+Ctrl+click or Shift+click on the image canvas to choose absolute or relative mode, respectively (see below). Finally click on the canvas to choose the area to be healed (the target area). A cross is displayed where the source area will be positioned.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The source positioning has two modes\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"absolute mode\n"
": Before placing a shape on the image canvas, Shift+Ctrl+click on the desired position for the source. From this point on, all new shapes will have their source created at the same absolute position (in image co-ordinates). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"relative mode\n"
": Before placing a shape on the image canvas, Shift+click on the desired position for the source. The current shape will have the source created at that position and subsequent shapes will have their source created at the same position, _relative to the target shape_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "After creation the source and target areas of each shape can be shifted independently until the result matches your expectations. An arrow points from the source area of each shape to its target.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Use the shape-specific controls to adjust each shape's size, border width, and other attributes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on a shape to delete it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/spot-removal.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module is equivalent to the \"cloning\" tool in the [_retouch_](./retouch.md) module; see the description of the cloning tool for additional details and examples.  If _spot removal_ produces unsatisfactory results, you may want to try the \"heal\" tool in _retouch_ instead.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/tone-mapping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "tone mapping (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/tone-mapping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_tone equalizer_](./tone-equalizer.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/tone-mapping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Compress the tonal range of HDR images so that they fit into the limits of an LDR image, using Durand's 2002 algorithm. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/tone-mapping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The underlying algorithm uses a bilateral filter to decompose an image into a coarse base layer and a detail layer. The contrast of the base layer is compressed, while the detail layer is preserved, then both layers are re-combined.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/tone-mapping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"contrast compression\n"
": The contrast compression level of the base layer. A higher compression will make the image fit a lower dynamic range.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/tone-mapping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"spatial extent\n"
": The spatial extent of the bilateral filter. Lower values cause the contrast compression to have stronger effects on image details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vibrance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "vibrance (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vibrance.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.6 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the vibrance control in the [_color balance rgb_](./color-balance-rgb.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vibrance.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Saturate and reduce the lightness of the most saturated pixels to make the colors more vivid.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/vibrance.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"vibrance\n"
": The amount of vibrance to apply to the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "zone system (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is [deprecated](../../darkroom/processing-modules/deprecated.md) from darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_tone equalizer_](./tone-equalizer.md) or multiple instances of the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module with [parametric masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) to narrow down on a zone.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Adjust the lightness of an image using Ansel Adams' [zone system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zone_System).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The lightness of the image (the L channel in Lab color space) is divided into a number of zones ranging from pure black to pure white. These zones are displayed in a zonebar beneath a preview image. The number of zones can be changed by mouse-scrolling on that bar (default 10 zones).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![zone-system](./zone-system/zone-system.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The zonebar is split horizontally with the lower part showing the zones of the module's input and the upper part the zones of the module's output. In its default state both parts are fully aligned. While the output zones are static you can left click and drag a control point in the input zones to modify the mapping between input and output. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Shifting a control point proportionally expands the zones on one side and compresses the zones on the other side of that point. All pre-existing control points stay in place, effectively preventing changes to the zones beyond the next control point. Use right click to remove a control point. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The preview image above the zonebar shows how the image's zones are broken down. When hovering above a zone, that zone – either from input or output – is highlighted in yellow on the preview image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "dithering"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module eliminates some of the banding artifacts that can result when darktable's internal 32-bit floating point data is transferred into discrete 8-bit or 16-bit integer output format for display or export.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Although not an inherent problem in any of darktable's modules, some operations may provoke banding if they produce a lightness gradient in the image. To mitigate possible artifacts you should consider activating dithering when using the [_vignetting_](./vignetting.md) or [_graduated density_](./graduated-density.md) modules. This is especially relevant for images with extended homogeneous areas such as cloudless sky. Also watch out for banding artifacts when using a gradient [drawn mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Viewing an image dithered into a very low bit depth from some distance (e.g. “floyd-steinberg 1-bit b&w”) will give the impression of a homogeneous grayscale image. darktable attempts to mimic this impression when rendering zoomed-out images in the center view, the navigation window and thumbnails. This is accomplished by dithering those images into a higher number of grayscale levels. Note that, as a consequence, the [scopes](../utility-modules/shared/scopes.md) module -- the data for which is derived from the navigation window -- will show this increased number of levels and is therefore not a full match to the output image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"method\n"
": Choose the dithering method to use. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": _floyd-steinberg_: Systematically distribute quantization errors over neighboring pixels. This method can be selected with some typical output bit depths. Alternatively, you can select _floyd-steinberg auto_, which automatically adapts to the desired output format.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": _random dithering_: This method just adds some level of randomness to break sharp tonal value bands. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/dithering.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"damping (\"random\" method only)\n"
": Controls the level of added random noise expressed as a damping factor in a 10*log 2 basis. A value of -80 is a good fit for 8-bit output formats; -160 for 16-bit output.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "blurs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate physically-accurate blurs in scene-referred RGB space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "blur types"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Three types of blur are provided:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_lens blur_: Simulates a lens diaphragm with a configurable number of blades and blade curvature to create synthetic bokeh.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_motion blur_: Simulates the effect of camera motion with a configurable path.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_gaussian blur_: This is not really an optical blur but can be used for denoising or for creative effects using [blend modes](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A diagram at the top of the module shows the shape of the blurring operator (known as the [_point spread function_](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_spread_function)). The module will turn each luminous point from the scene into a blot shaped like the displayed blurring operator, with the size of the blot defined by the _blur radius_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#: content/preferences-settings/general.md
#: content/preferences-settings/lighttable.md
#: content/preferences-settings/security.md
#: content/preferences-settings/darkroom.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "general"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blur radius\n"
": The spreading size of the blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blur type\n"
": Choose between the different blur variants (above).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "controls specific to lens blur"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"diaphragm blades\n"
": The number of blades that the diaphragm is composed of. Older lenses used typically 5 or 7 blades, newer lenses typically use 9 or 11 blades. In any case, real lenses have an odd number of blades and any number greater than 11 blades comes very close to producing a perfect disc. If you degenerate the diaphragm settings with the _concavity_ to create a star or an asterisk, this control defines how many branches it has.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"concavity\n"
": - a concavity of 1 ensures the diaphragm is a [regular convex polygon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon#Regular_convex_polygons) (triangle, pentagon, heptagon, etc.).\n"
": - a concavity greater than 1 but lower than `number of blades - 1` turns the shape into a star.\n"
": - a concavity greater than `number of blades - 1` but lower than `number of blades` turns the shape into an asterisk, when decreasing _linearity_ below 1.\n"
": - a concavity greater than or equal to `number of blades` degenerates the shape into a \"burst pattern\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linearity\n"
": - a linearity of 0 creates a disc, no matter the number of blades or the concavity.\n"
": - a linearity of 1 makes all the outer bounds of the shape straight.\n"
": - a linearity between 0 and 1 makes the outer bounds of the shape more or less curved.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rotation\n"
": Allows the shape to be rotated with respect to its center -- mostly useful with a small number of blades, when a particular orientation is needed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "controls specific to motion blur"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"direction\n"
": The orientation of the motion's path in angular degrees. 0° is horizontal motion.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"curvature\n"
": The curvature of the motion. Zero produces a straight line, a negative value produces a concave curvature, a positive value produces a convex curvature.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"offset\n"
": Shifts along the motion path following its curve. This is useful to select a portion of the curved path that is symmetrical, which produces a coma shape (example 1: direction = -45°, curvature = +2, offset = +0.5 ; example 2 : direction = -45°, curvature = +1, offset = +1).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module is implemented using a \"naive\" convolution, which is a slow algorithm. Faster approaches are available (using FFT) but not yet implemented. The GPU implementation, through OpenCL, should hide this issue somewhat. In any case, the runtime of the module will increase with the square of the blur radius.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The blurring process does not take scene depth and depth-of-field into account, but blurs the whole image as a flat object. It is therefore not suitable for creating fake depth-of-field. Using darktable's general masking will only partially work to isolate the foreground of an image, since it will still be blurred into the background.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "tips and tricks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/blurs.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "All images are usually (even a tiny bit) noisy. If you blur only a part of the image, the blurred region will look suspiciously clean compared to the rest of the image. It is therefore a good idea to add a bit of noise on top of the blurred part to blend it with the rest, using either the [grain](./grain.md) or the [censorize](./censorize.md) modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color balance rgb"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "An advanced module which brings color-grading tools from cinematography into the photographic scene-referred pipeline. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module is not suitable for beginners with no prior knowledge of color theory, who might want to stick to the _global chroma_ and _global vibrance_ settings until they have a good understanding of the [dimensions of color](../../special-topics/color-management/color-dimensions.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#: content/overview/workflow/introduction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Color-grading is an important part of image editing. It can help to remove unwanted color casts and can also deliver a creative color twist that will add atmosphere to your images. In the days of film photography, most of the color ambiance was obtained with the film emulsion and the developing chemicals, with some color timing being performed under the enlarger with color heads. This consumed expensive resources and was mostly reserved for the cinema industry, where the job was performed by a colorist.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In the digital age, where raw images look flat and even, color-grading assumes the same role that film emulsions did, by re-introducing color shifts for aesthetic purposes. It can also serve to harmonize the color palette of a series of images (which may have been shot under different conditions) to achieve a consistent global look. For this task, the [vectorscope](../utility-modules/shared/scopes.md#vectorscope) is also extremely useful.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Colorists usually split color-grading into two distinct steps:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_Primary color-grading_ aims to fix unwanted color casts and create a neutral starting point,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_Secondary color-grading_ gives the image its final look and atmosphere.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Primary color-grading is best left to the [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module, which operates in a physical framework better suited to illuminant correction. _Color balance RGB_, on the other hand, is mostly concerned with secondary color-grading. Performing a truly neutral primary color-grading should make the secondary color-grading easy to transfer between images (via styles, presets or copy & paste) with a similar effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "general principles"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _color balance RGB_ module is an improvement over the [American Society of Cinematographers Color Decision List](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASC_CDL) (ASC CDL), and uses alpha masks to allow the effect to be properly split between shadows and highlights. The classic CDL acts on the entire luminance range, and each of its parameters is given more weight on some parts of the image only as a side-effect of the mathematics.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module works, for the most part (_4 ways_, _chroma_, _vibrance_, _contrast_), in a linear RGB color space designed specifically for color-grading. This color space exhibits a uniform spacing of perceptual hues while retaining a physically-scaled luminance[^1]. The perceptual part of the module (_saturation_ and _brilliance_) works in the JzAzBz[^2] color space, which provides a perceptual scaling of both lightness and chromaticity suitable for HDR images. Both color spaces ensure that saturation and chroma changes take place at constant hue, which is not the case for most other saturation operators in darktable (notably in the older [_color balance_](./color-balance.md) module).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "[^1]: Richard A. Kirk, Chromaticity coordinates for graphic arts based on CIE 2006 LMS with even spacing of Munsell colours, 2019. <https://doi.org/10.2352/issn.2169-2629.2019.27.38>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "[^2]: Safdar et al., Perceptually uniform color space for image signals including high dynamic range and wide gamut, 2017. <https://doi.org/10.1364/OE.25.015131>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _color balance RGB_ module expects a scene-referred linear input and produces a scene-referred RGB output, which may or may not be linear, depending on the module settings (_contrast_ and _power_ will delinearize the output).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At its output, _color balance RGB_ checks that the graded colors fit inside the pipeline RGB color space (Rec 2020 by default) and applies a soft saturation clipping at constant hue, aiming to retarget out-of-gamut color to the nearest in-gamut color by scaling both chroma and lightness. This prevents the chroma and saturation settings from pushing colors outside of the valid range and allows more drastic adjustments to be safely used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_Note that this module abides by the CIE definitions of chroma and saturation, as explained in the [dimensions of color](../../special-topics/color-management/color-dimensions.md) section._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "master tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue shift\n"
": Rotate all colors in the image by an angle over the chromaticity plane, at constant luminance and chroma. You can use this control to remove spilled colored light on a subject or to quickly change the color of some object. This setting is usually best applied locally, using [masks](../../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"global vibrance\n"
": This affects the chroma dimension of color over the entire image, prioritizing those colors with low chroma. This allows the chroma of neutral colors to be increased without exaggerating already-colorful pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"contrast\n"
": This setting is applied on the luminance channel at constant hue and chroma. The fulcrum setting (in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab, under _contrast gray fulcrum_) allows you to set the neutral point of the contrast curve:\n"
": - at the fulcrum, the contrast curve leaves the luminance unchanged,\n"
": - below the fulcrum, the contrast curve decreases the luminance for positive contrast values, or increases it for negative values,\n"
": - above the fulcrum, the contrast curve increases the luminance for positive contrast values, or decreases it for negative values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": The fulcrum has a value of 18.45% by default, which is consistent with the current scene-referred workflow and should fit most use cases (assuming that global brightness has been fixed as recommended using the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": The contrast algorithm gives natural results that mimic the central part of the contrast curve of analog film. However, it will also increase the image's dynamic range, which may void _filmic_ settings in the pipe. For global contrast adjustments, you should normally use the [_tone equalizer_](./tone-equalizer.md) module -- the _color balance RGB_ contrast slider is best used with masks, e.g. for selective corrections over the foreground or background.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "linear chroma grading"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Linear chroma grading affects the chroma dimension proportionally to its input value, at constant hue and luminance. It does this globally, with a flat coefficient (using the _global chroma_), as well as on each of the _shadows_, _mid-tones_ and _highlights_ masks (defined in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _luminance ranges_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "perceptual saturation grading"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Perceptual saturation grading affects both the luminance and the chroma dimensions, in a perceptual space, proportionally to its input value, at constant hue. It does this globally, with a flat coefficient (using the _global saturation_), as well as on each of the _shadows_, _mid-tones_ and _highlights_ masks (defined in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _luminance ranges_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "perceptual brilliance grading"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Perceptual brilliance grading affects both the luminance and the chroma dimensions, in a perceptual space, proportionally to its input value, at constant hue, and in a direction orthogonal to the saturation. Its effect is close to that of changing exposure, but scaled perceptually. It does this globally, with a flat coefficient (using the _global saturation_), as well as on each of the _shadows_, _mid-tones_ and _highlights_ masks (defined in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _luminance ranges_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "4 ways tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each of the settings in the 4 ways tab is composed of the same three components, which define a color using independent coordinates:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_luminance_,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_hue_,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_chroma_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Color input like this defines a color shift applied to the image globally or over the specified luminance range.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each hue slider has a color-picker, which may be used to compute the opponent color of the selected region. This is useful to revert unwanted color casts (e.g. skin redness), since shifting the color to its opponent cast neutralizes it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "global offset"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This is equivalent to the ASC CDL _offset_ and falls back to adding a constant RGB value to all pixels, quite like the _black offset_ in the _exposure_ module. This control does not use masking.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "shadows lift"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This is conceptually equivalent to the _lift_ from _lift/gamma/gain_, although implemented differently, and falls back to multiplying the masked pixels by a constant RGB value. It is applied using the _shadows_ mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "highlights gain"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This is equivalent to the ASC CDL _slope_, and falls back to multiplying a the masked pixels by a constant RGB value. It is applied using the _highlights_ mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "global power"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This is equivalent to the ASC CDL _power_, and falls back to applying a constant RGB exponent. It is not masked and needs to be normalized, since the power function has a different behaviour above and below 1, and we are in an unbounded pipeline where white is typically greater than 1. The normalization parameter is available in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _white fulcrum_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "masks tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This tab defines auxiliary controls for the previous tabs. Masking controls typically don't require any user modification since the defaults are calibrated to suit most needs and fulfil the normal scene-referred pixel pipeline expectations. You should only need to change these settings in specific scenarios.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "luminance ranges"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The graphs show the opacity (on the _y_ axis) of the 3 luminance masks relative to the pixel luminance (on the _x_ axis). The darkest curve represents the _shadows_ mask, the brightest represents the _highlights_ mask, and the third curve represents the _mid-tones_ mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Only the _shadows_ and _highlights_ masks can be controlled directly -- the _mid-tones_ mask is computed indirectly from the others and acts as an adjustment variable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shadows fall-off\n"
": Control the softness or hardness of the transition from fully opaque (100%) to fully transparent (0%) for the shadows mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mask middle-gray fulcrum\n"
": Set the luminance value where all three masks have 50% opacity. In practice, this is used to define how the image is separated into shadows and highlights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"highlights fall-off\n"
": Control the softness or hardness of the transition from fully opaque (100%) to fully transparent (0%) for the highlights mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "For each of these settings, a mask button, provided to the right of the slider, displays the appropriate mask (shadows, mid-tones, highlights), overlaid as a checker board. The still-visible area of the image (not hidden by the mask) is the area that will be affected by the shadows, mid-tones and highlights sliders in the other tabs.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "All mask previews display the output of the module, including any color changes made, so you can also activate them while editing, to see only the affected part of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Luminance masks are computed at the input of the module, which means that they are insensitive to any luminance changes made inside the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "thresholds"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"white fulcrum\n"
": Set the white point luminance in EV. This is used to normalize the _power_ setting in the [_4 ways_](#4-ways-tab) tab. Display-referred implementations of power functions assume that white is at 100%, which removes the need for normalization. For scene-referred purposes this needs to be taken into account.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": The color-picker to the right of the slider automatically sets the white fulcrum to the maximum luminance from the selected region, which should be sufficient in most cases.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"contrast gray fulcrum\n"
": Set the fulcrum for the _contrast_ setting in the [_master_](#master-tab) tab. This corresponds to the luminance value that will be left unchanged by the contrast adjustment. This setting usually matches the middle-gray linear value. If you followed the scene-referred workflow recommendations and set the global brightness early in the pipeline, using the _exposure_ module, the correct value should usually be around 18-20%.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": The color-picker to the right of the slider automatically sets the contrast gray fulcrum to the average luminance from the selected region. This relies on the assumption that the average luminance is usually close to middle-gray, which is not true if you have specular highlights or primary light sources in the frame, or for low/high-key images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "mask preview settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These settings apply to the mask previews, displayed by clicking the mask buttons in the _luminance ranges_ section. These settings are saved globally, so will be applied to all subsequent images unless changed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"checker board color 1 and 2\n"
": Set the two colors for the background checker board mask underlay. You can set them to opponent colors of the current image to aid legibility.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"checker board size\n"
": Set the width of the checker board cells in pixels (adjusted according to the display's DPI setting).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "FAQ"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "saturation or chroma?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As described in the [dimensions of color](../../special-topics/color-management/color-dimensions.md) section, saturation and chroma roam the (lightness, chroma) plane in different directions. In addition, the chroma of _color balance RGB_ uses a scene-referred linear space, while the saturation uses a perceptual space, which rescales color for even spacing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In practice, you should use the chroma setting if you want to preserve the scene-linearity of the light emission and/or keep the luminance unchanged. However, these changes might affect some hues more heavily than others, due to the fact that the color space is not fully perceptually-scaled.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Saturation is closer to the effect of mixing white paint with some base color. Reducing the saturation of red will degrade it to pink, while reducing its chroma will degrade to a gray shade at the same luminance. Saturation is perhaps a more intuitive way to interact with color, due to its connection with painting.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Choosing one or the other is mostly a matter of deciding where on the (lightness, chroma) graph you want to push your colors, and where they are to begin with. To reach pastel colors, saturation is the way to go. To reach laser-like colors (almost monochromatic), at the risk of looking synthetic, chroma is the way to go.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "what is the connection with lift/gamma/gain?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _lift/gamma/gain_ algorithm relies on a display-referred color space, since it assumes a bounded and symmetric dynamic range, with white point at 100% and gray at 50%. As such, it is simply unusable in a scene-referred space. However, the only incompatible part is the _lift_. The _gamma_ is exactly the ASC CDL _power_, and the _gain_ is exactly the ASC CDL _slope_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _color balance RGB_ module simply has two slopes instead of one: the _gain_, applied on the highlights extracted from the whole image by a mask, and the _lift_, applied similarly but on the shadows.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "changing contrast"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "While _color balance RGB_ is mostly about color (other modules handle the global contrast in chromaticity-preserving ways) luminance is as much a part of color as hue or chroma, and it needs to be dealt with here too, because the perception of saturation relies on it. If you wish to turn red into pink, for example, reducing its chroma will turn it gray, so you need to increase its luminance as well.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "There are several ways to change the contrast in _color balance RGB_, either locally (with masks) or globally (without):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "in the [_master_](#master-tab) tab, use the _contrast_ setting (possibly alongside the _contrast gray fulcrum_ in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab). Be aware that this will raise the white point and therefore increase the dynamic range of the image, which may void filmic settings later in the pipeline.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "in [_perceptual saturation grading_](#perceptual-saturation-grading), desaturate highlights and resaturate shadows to produce a luminance contrast boost,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "in [_perceptual brilliance grading_](#perceptual-brilliance-grading), add brilliance in the highlights and remove brilliance in the shadows to produce to a luminance contrast boost,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "in the [_4 ways_](#4-ways-tab) tab, set the _shadows lift_ luminance to negative values and the _highlights gain_ luminance to positive values, which also produces a luminance contrast boost.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The difference between these methods is how the effect will be weighted relative to the input of the module. You are advised to do the majority of luminance contrast adjustments in the _filmic_ and _tone equalizer_ modules, and then undertake final changes in _color balance RGB_ while examining the colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "internal processing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following is the internal order of operations within the module:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Transform from pipeline RGB to Kirk/Filmlight Ych space,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Apply hue shift at constant chroma and constant luminance,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Compute luminance masks with Y,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Apply the _linear chroma_ and _vibrance_ settings at constant hue and luminance,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Transform to Kirk/Filmlight RGB space,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Apply the _4 ways_ settings (except _luminance power_),\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '7. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Transform to Kirk/Filmlight Yrg space,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '8. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Apply _luminance power_ and _contrast_ on Y,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '9. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Transform to JzAzBz space,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '10. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Apply the _perceptual saturation_ and _perceptual brilliance_ settings,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '11. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Soft-clip the chroma using pipeline RGB gamut at constant hue and lightness,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '12. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Transform back to pipeline RGB.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Setting the global chroma to -100% will not produce a real monochrome image, as is customary with other algorithms. The reason for this is that the RGB space used has a D65 white point defined in CIE LMS 2006 space, while darktable uses a white point defined in CIE XYZ 1931 space, and there is no exact conversion between these spaces. The result will therefore be a slighly tinted black & white image. If your intent is to get a real black & white image using the luminance channel, the _color calibration_ module offers a _B&W : luminance-based_ preset that does exactly the same thing but without the white-point discrepancy.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module has its gamut-mapping (against pipeline RGB) permanently enabled. This means that if your original image contains some largely out-of-gamut colors to start with, simply enabling _color balance RGB_ with no particular setting will slightly alter its colors. This is probably for the best.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The maximum saturation allowed in the pipeline working RGB space is recorded for each hue when initializing the module, and is later cached in a LUT (look-up table) to save performance. If the working profile is later changed, _color balance RGB_ is not notified, meaning that it will not update its cached hue/saturation LUT. To force a LUT update, you can simply change any setting in the _color balance RGB_ module, then change it back again. It is not recommended that you change the working RGB space half-way through an editing session, as this could result in unexpected chroma and hue changes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "For performance reasons, the non-linear conversions from and to the working RGB space are bypassed, meaning that the internal colorimetry will be wrong when using non-linear color spaces. Note that there is no reason to use non-linear spaces as working RGB since they make alpha blending more challenging for no benefit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color zones"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Selectively adjust the lightness, saturation and hue of pixels based on their current lightness, saturation and hue.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module works in CIE LCh color space, which separates pixels into _lightness_, chroma (_saturation_) and _hue_ components. It allows you to manipulate the lightness, saturation and hue of targeted groups of pixels through the use of [curves](../../darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You first need to choose whether you wish to adjust (select) pixels based on their lightness, saturation or hue. You can then use three curves, on their respective tabs, to adjust the lightness, saturation and hue of ranges of pixels selected via this method.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_**Note:** This module should be used with care, as transitions between colors may not be graceful. Instead, use the [color balance rgb](./color-balance-rgb.md) module with a [parametric mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md)._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "pixel selection method"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _color zones_ module offers three different methods for selecting which pixels you want to adjust. They are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by hue (default)\n"
": Select pixels to manipulate based on their hue. For example, you may want to darken a blue sky, or to change a red porche into a yellow one. The following image shows the full range of hues that you can choose to operate on:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![color zones choose hue](./color-zones/color-zones-choose-hue.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by lightness\n"
": Select pixels to manipulate based on their lightness. For example, you may want to make your shadows brighter, or to make your highlights more yellow. The following image shows the range of lightness levels that you can choose to operate on, from dark to light:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![color zones choose lightness](./color-zones/color-zones-choose-lightness.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by saturation\n"
": Select pixels to manipulate based on their saturation. For example, you may want to tone down the saturation of some already highly saturated pixels, or to change their hue. The following image shows the range of saturation levels that you can choose to operate on, from a completely unsaturated monochrome gray through to the most highly saturated color:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![color zones choose saturation](./color-zones/color-zones-choose-saturation.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "pixel manipulation curves"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have chosen a pixel selection method, the selected range of lightness, saturation or hue levels will appear along the horizontal axis of the three pixel manipulation curves, which can be viewed and adjusted by choosing the appropriate tab (lightness, saturation, hue). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If, for example, you were to choose to _select by hue_ (the default), the horizontal axis (below the manipulation curves) would show the range of hues you can work with, and the three pixel manipulation curves would appears as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lightness\n"
": By adjusting the lightness curve up or down in a given (hue) location, you can brighten or darken pixels matching hues where the curve has been raised or lowered, respectively. In the example below the blue sky in an image has been darkened for dramatic effect:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![color zones adjust lightness](./color-zones/color-zones-adjust-lightness.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": By adjusting the saturation curve up or down in a given (hue) location, you can desaturate (make less colorful) or resaturate (make more colorful) pixels matching hues where the curve has been raised or lowered, respectively. In the example below, a red object in the background has been desaturated so it is less of a distraction to the main subject of the photo:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![color zones adjust saturation](./color-zones/color-zones-adjust-saturation.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": By adjusting the hue curve up or down in a given (hue) location, you can shift the hue of pixels matching hues where the curve has been raised or lowered, allowing you to replace one color with another. In the example below, a pink toy in an image has been changed to blue:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![color zones adjust hue](./color-zones/color-zones-adjust-hue.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The curves work similarly in the lightness- and saturation-based selection modes as well. See the section on [curves](../../darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md) to see how spline curves work in general.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Note that these examples are somewhat contrived in order to illustrate the module's usage. In practical use, they would likely need to be combined with [drawn](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) and/or [parametric](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) masks to further isolate their effect. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "range selection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When adjusting the pixel manipulation curves, it can sometimes be difficult to judge exactly where on the horizontal axis pixels will fall. To the right of the tab controls are a pair of color pickers that can be used to assist with this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If you click the left-hand color picker and choose a pixel in the image, you will see a dark vertical line showing where that pixel falls on the horizontal axis. If you Ctrl+click or right-click on the same color picker you can choose a rectangular area from the image -- the range of values represented within the selected rectangle will be shaded vertically, with a similar dark line showing the median value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If you click on the right-hand color picker, you can similarly choose a rectangular area on the image and the display will be shown as described above (a shaded area with a dark vertical line). However, in this case the color picker will also automatically add some control points to the curve for you, representing the highlighted range (see below). Simply drag on the center node to raise or lower the curve within the selected range. Alternatively, hold Ctrl while selecting a range to automatically create a positive curve (push up the selected range) or hold Shift while selecting to create a negative curve (pushed down). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![color zones overview](./color-zones/color-zones-overview.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following controls are available in the _color zones_ module:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lightness, saturation & hue tabs\n"
": Each tab displays a pixel manipulation curve to allow you to alter “lightness”, “saturation”, or “hue” based on the pixel selection method.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"edit by area\n"
": Choose how to interact with the curve. This setting is disabled by default, allowing the control points for the curve to be freely placed. Check the box to fall back to the legacy \"edit by area\" mode, which functions in a similar way to the spline curve controls used in [wavelet](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md#spline-controls) modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
" ![mask-icon](./color-zones/icon-mask.png#icon) mask display\n"
": Enable the _mask display_ to highlight pixels that have been affected by _color zones_ adjustments in yellow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by\n"
": Define the horizontal axis (the range of values to work on). You can choose between “lightness”, “saturation”, and “hue” (the default). Changing this parameter resets all pixel manipulation curves to their default state (horizontal straight lines). If you want to work on multiple ranges, you need to create additional instances of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"process mode\n"
": Choose between a “smooth” (default) or “strong” processing mode. The default mode is less likely to cause artifacts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mix\n"
": Use this parameter to tune the strength of the overall effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-zones.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"interpolation method\n"
": Define how the curve is interpolated using the user-defined control points. See the [curves](../../darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md) section for more details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "contrast equalizer"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Adjust luminance and chroma contrast in the wavelet domain.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This versatile module can be used to achieve a variety of effects, including bloom, denoise, clarity, and local contrast enhancement. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "It works in the [wavelet](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md) domain and its parameters can be tuned independently for each wavelet detail scale. The module operates in CIE LCh color space and so is able to treat luminosity and chromaticity independently.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A number of presets are provided, which should help you to understand the capabilities of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _contrast equalizer_ module decomposes the image into various detail scales. On each detail scale, you can independently adjust the contrast and denoise splines for lightness (\"luma\") and chromaticity (“chroma”, or color saturation), as well as adjusting the edge-awareness (“edges”) of the wavelet transform. The luma, chroma and edges splines are provided on separate tabs, and some examples of their usage are given in the following sections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Below the spline graphs is a _mix_ slider, which can be used to adjust the strength of the effect, and even to invert the graph (with negative values). While your mouse is over the spline graph, the curve will be displayed as if the _mix_ slider was set to 1.0, to allow for easier editing. When you move your mouse away, the graph will be re-adjusted to account for the _mix_ slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In the background of the curve you can see a number of alternating light and dark stripes. These represent the levels of detail that are visible at your current zoom scale -- any details without these stripes are too small to be seen your current view. Adjustments made to control points within the striped section _may_ produce a visible effect (depending on the strength of the adjustment). Adjustments outside of the striped region _will not_. Zoom in to see higher levels of detail and make adjustments to the more detailed areas of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Tip:** if you are having trouble visualising which parts of the curve will affect which details in the image, you can set the [blend mode](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md) to \"difference\". This will make the image go black except for those areas where the output of the module differs from the input. By raising the curve at one of the control points, you will be able to see which details in the image are represented by that point.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "luma tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The luma tab allows you to adjust the local contrast in the image's luminance (brightness). Adjustments are represented by a white spline that begins as a horizontal line running across the centre of the graph (indicating that no change will be made). Raise or lower this spline at the left end of the graph to increase or decrease the local contrast of coarse detail in the image. Perform similar adjustments towards the right side of the graph to adjust the local contrast of the fine details in the image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When you hover the mouse pointer over the graph, a white circle indicates the radius of influence of the mouse pointer -- the size of this circle can be adjusted by scrolling with the mouse wheel. The larger the circle of influence, the more control points will be affected when you adjust the curve. A highlighted region in the background shows what the spline would look like if you pushed the currently-hovered control point all the way to the top or bottom on the graph -- see the screenshot below for examples of these features. For more information see the [wavelets](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md) section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following image shows the default state of the contrast equalizer module before any adjustments have been made:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![contrast-equalizer-luma-orig](./contrast-equalizer/contrast-equalizer-luma-orig.png#w66)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Raising the two control points at the right-hand end of the graph will increase the sharpness of the fine details (the eye and feathers of the bird) while leaving coarser details (the rocks in the background) largely unaffected. The example below has been exaggerated to better illustrate the effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![contrast-equalizer-luma-high](./contrast-equalizer/contrast-equalizer-luma-high.png#w66)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Increasing the local contrast can also amplify the luma noise in the image. A second spline located at the bottom of the graph can be used used to denoise the selected detail scales. Raise this spline (by clicking just above one of the triangles at the bottom of the graph and dragging the line upwards) to reduce noise at the given wavelet scale. In the example above, the dark denoising spline has been raised at the fine-detail end of the graph.\n"
msgstr ""

