#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "clipping warning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Highlight areas of the image that may exhibit luminance or gamut clipping.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When an image is sent to a display device, each pixel is normally represented as a set of 3 numbers, representing the intensity of the red, green and blue primary colors in the output color space. Because the output color space is usually closely related to hardware with physical limations, there is a maximum permitted value for the [R,G,B] channels, representing the maximum available intensity for that color space. Similarly, there is also a minimum value below which pixel values will be mapped to zero. When we try to convert from a larger color space to the final output color space, any values exceeding this maximum will be clamped to the maximum value, and any values below the minimum will be clamped to zero. This process is called \"clipping\" and it will lead to lost detail, or \"incorrect\" colors for any pixels with clipped channels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the ![clipping warning](./clipping/clipping-icon.png#icon) icon to enable the clipping warning.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "There are two ways in which a pixel might become clipped when represented in the output color space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_luminance clipping_: This can occur when a pixel is too bright to be represented in the output color space. The pixel luminance is calculated as a weighted average of the [R,G,B] channels. If this average exceeds the maximum allowed value, it is an indication of over-exposure. The overall luminance of a pixel can also be too dark to be represented by an [R,G,B] value in the output color space, in which case it will simply be shown as black. We normally deal with luminance clipping by carefully adjusting tone mappings and exposure levels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_gamut clipping_: The output color space defines a set of primary colors that, mixed together in certain ratios, produce the final output color. However, there are only so many colors that can be produced by mixing together a combination of those three primary colors. Highly saturated colors in particular can be difficult to represent, especially for pixels that are very bright or very dark. If there is no set of positive [R,G,B] values that can represent a given color at a given level of brightness, we say that the color is \"out of gamut\", and we need to settle for another color instead that _can_ be represented by permitted [R,G,B] values within the color space. We can handle gamut clipping by being careful not to over-saturate colors in the highlights and shadows, and possibly by using some color grading/color mapping techniques.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The \"clipping warning\" module is used to highlight those pixels that cannot be accurately represented in the output color space, either due to luminance or gamut clipping. Prior to darktable 3.4, the clipping highlighted any pixels that exceeded the maximum allowed value on any of the [R,G,B] channels, or that had been completely crushed to black. From darktable 3.4 onwards, the clipping warning indicator has some additional modes to help you to differentiate between luminance and gamut clipping, so that you can make better decisions about how to address any issues.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As the clipping warning runs at the end of the preview pixelpipe, it receives data in display color space then converts it to histogram color space. If you are using a display color space that is not \"well behaved\" (this is common for a device profile), then colors that are outside of the gamut of the display profile will clip or distort.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The clipping warning module, described here, warns you about clipping caused by image processing and the limitations of the output color space. It should not be confused with the following similar tools:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The [raw overexposed warning](./raw-overexposed.md) indicates where pixels in the original raw file are clipped due to physical limitations in the dynamic range of the camera sensor. This module highlights information that was permanently lost at the point of image capture, and you need to deal with it as best you can using highlight recovery techniques.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The [gamut check](./gamut.md) module also provides information about clipping arising from image processing. It is based on the external littleCMS library, and is more or less equivalent to the _full gamut_ mode in the clipping warning module. The downsides of the gamut check module are that it doesn't allow you to distinguish between clipping caused by luminance and gamut mapping, and it is much slower than the clipping warning indicator.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on the clipping icon to show the following options:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clipping preview mode\n"
": Choose the type of clipping that you want to highlight:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _any RGB channel_: Provides an over-clipping indication if any one of the three [R,G,B] channels exceeds the maximum permitted value for the histogram color space, or an under-clipping indication if the three [R,G,B] channels are too dark and are all forced to black. This was the default mode prior to darktable version 3.4.\n"
": - _luminance only_: Indicates any pixels that are clipped because their luminance falls outside of the range set in the \"upper threshold\" and \"lower threshold\" sliders. If this happens, it generally means that tone mapping or exposure settings have been poorly set\n"
": - _saturation only_: Indicates where over-saturated colors have pushed one or more of the [R,G,B] channels towards a value outside the permitted range of the histogram color space, even though the overall luminance of the pixel may lie within acceptable limits. This means that the pixel's color is impossible to represent in the histogram color space, and can arise from poorly set gamut mapping or saturation settings,\n"
": - _full gamut_: Shows a combination of the three previous options. This is the default mode from darktable 3.4 onwards, and it gives the most complete indication of potentially problematic pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color scheme\n"
": By default, the indicator marks pixels with _red_ where the upper threshold is exceeded (over-clipping) and with _blue_ where the lower threshold is breached (under-clipping). This color scheme can be changed to _black & white_ or _purple & green_ for \"over & under\" indicators, which may be useful to improve visibility for some images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lower threshold\n"
": Expressed in EV relative to the white point (which is nominally EV = 0). If the [R,G,B] channels all fall below this value, an under-clipping indicator is shown warning that the pixel may be end up being crushed to black. Use the following reference to set this threshold, depending on your intended output medium:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _8-bit sRGB_ clips blacks at --12.69 EV\n"
": - _8-bit Adobe RGB_ clips blacks at --19.79 EV\n"
": - _16-bit sRGB_ clips blacks at --20.69 EV\n"
": - _fine art matte prints_ typically produce black at --5.30 EV\n"
": - _color glossy prints_ typically produce black at --8.00 EV\n"
": - _black & white glossy prints_ typically produce black at --9.00 EV\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/clipping.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"upper threshold\n"
": How close a pixel should be to the upper limit before being flagged by the clipping warning, expressed as a percentage (default 98%). In the case of gamut checks, this controls how close the saturation of the pixel is allowed to get to the limits of the color space's gamut before a clipping indication is flagged.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "mask manager"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Manage all masks and shapes for the current image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![mask manager](./mask-manager/mask-manager.png#w25)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module can be used to create, rename, edit and delete shapes. You can add shapes to and remove shapes from a mask, group shapes together, and combine them using set operators. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The top line of the mask manager panel contains buttons that can be used to create new shapes. These are the same as in the [drawn mask](../../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) interface of in processing modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The panel below these buttons displays a list of all masks and individual shapes defined for the current image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Groups of shapes forming a mask are displayed with a headline in the form \"grp <module_name>\" indicating the module in which they are used, with the component shapes listed below. The list of mask groups is followed by a list of all individual shapes that have been generated in the context of the current image. If a shape is in use by any masks this is indicated by a symbol to the right of the shape name. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default each shape receives an automatically generated name, consisting of the shape type (\"brush\", \"circle\", \"ellipse\", \"path\", \"gradient\") and an automatically-incremented integer. You can rename a shape by double-clicking on its current name. It is a good habit to give shapes and groups meaningful names, especially if you intend to re-use the same selection in different masks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on a shape name to show the selected shape on the image canvas with all of its controls, allowing you to edit the properties of just that shape. This is especially useful where there are many overlapping shapes within a mask, making it difficult to select the right one with the mouse. Similarly if you select a shape on-screen from within the mask controls of a processing module, that shape will be selected in the mask manager.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on a shape name to show a menu containing options to remove the current shape or to remove all shapes not currently in use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** darktable retains all shapes that have ever been defined for the current image unless you explicitly remove them. If you choose to include develop history when exporting an image, all defined shapes will be exported with the image. Beware that if the list of shapes is very long the space required to store those shapes might exceed the size limit of certain file formats. This can cause XMP tag creation to fail during export.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "masks & groups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Masks are constructed by adding a group of shapes to the image in the order that they are listed (from top to bottom). Each shape adjusts the existing mask using one of four logical set operators (see below). Because order is important it is also possible to move shapes up and down the list.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the name of a group in the mask manager to expand that group, showing a list of its constituent shapes. The corresponding shapes will be shown on the center image. Similarly if you choose to show a mask from within a processing module, the corresponding group will be expanded within the mask manager.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on the group name to display a menu with options to add new or existing shapes to the group, or to clean up unused shapes. You can also choose to delete the group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on any of the constituent shapes to control how that shape contributes to the overall group mask:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"remove from group\n"
": Remove the shape from the current mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"use inverted shape\n"
": Invert the polarity of the selected shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": Choose how this shape will interact with the preceding mask by selecting one of the four set operators defined below.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"move up/down\n"
": Move the shape up or down the list.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You can also create your own groups using existing shapes by selecting the shapes you wish to group, right-clicking them and choosing \"group the forms\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "set operators"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Set operators are used to define how grouped shapes are combined. In the following examples we will use a mask that combines a gradient followed by a path, to demonstrate the effect of each set operator when applied to the path shape. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![gradient](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex1.png#w33#inline) ![path](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex2.png#w33#inline)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As a convention we say that a pixel is “selected” in a mask or shape if it has an opacity greater than zero. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"union\n"
": This is the default set operator and is depicted by the ![union-icon](./mask-manager/masks_union.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. The shape adds to the existing mask in such a way that the resulting mask contains the pixels that are *either* selected in the existing mask *or* in the added shape. In overlapping areas the maximum value is taken: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![union](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex3.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"intersection\n"
": This set operator is depicted by the ![intersection-icon](./mask-manager/masks_intersection.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. The shape adds to the existing mask in such a way that the resulting mask contains only pixels that are selected in *both* the existing mask *and* the added shape. In overlapping areas the minimum value is used. In the given example we use this operator to “imprint” the path with a gradient: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![intersection](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex4.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"difference\n"
": This set operator is depicted by the ![difference-icon](./mask-manager/masks_difference.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. In the non-overlapping area the existing mask is unchanged. In the resulting mask, pixels are selected only if they are selected in the existing mask but *not* in the added shape. This set operator can be chosen if you want to “cut out” a region from within an existing selection: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![difference](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex5.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exclusion\n"
": This set operator is depicted by the ![exclusion-icon](./mask-manager/masks_exclusion.png#icon) symbol to the left of the shape name. The resulting mask selects all pixels that are selected in the existing mask and not in the added shape or vice versa. This is equivalent to an “exclusive or”: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![exclusion](./mask-manager/mask-manager_ex6.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

