#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "places and folders"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The import dialog is intended to allow you to set up common import locations, to make subsequent imports as simple as possible. When you first open the dialog, darktable attempts to add some common locations (home, pictures, mounted devices) to the places pane. You can add new places to the list by clicking on the + button and you can remove places from the list by right-clicking on them. If you wish to restore a default location that you have deleted, you can do this with the reset button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When you choose a place, the folder tree is automatically populated (into the folders pane) from the root directory of the selected place. You can then navigate the folder tree and select a folder for import. The last selected place/folder is automatically reloaded the next time you open the dialog.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In the example screenshot above, you can see that a \"place\" has been created for the root of the Pictures folder and a sub-folder within that structure has been selected. This is the recommended workflow for the import process -- you should not have to create new places very often.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/collections.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have selected a folder, the files pane will automatically be populated with a list of the files found in that folder. By default, all files in the chosen folder are selected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You can view thumbnails for any of the images by clicking on the ![eye icon](./import/eye-icon.png#icon) icon. In addition, buttons are available at the bottom of the screen to select \"all\" files or \"none\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once you are happy with your selection, press Enter or click on the button at the bottom-right of the screen to import (this button will be named differently depending on the type of import being performed).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Press Escape or click the \"cancel\" button to exit without importing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "common options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following additional options are common to all import dialogs:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"recursive directory\n"
": Check this option to import images in the selected folder _and all subfolders_. It is recommended that you not use this option to import a large number of images at the same time. The import process causes darktable to generate thumbnails for all of the imported images, but in the end it will only be able to keep the most recent in its cache. It is therefore better to import images in smaller chunks to avoid the performance penalty this imposes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ignore JPEG images\n"
": Check this option if there are `JPEG` images in the same folder that you do not wish to import. This option is usually used where the camera stores `RAW+JPEG` and you only want to work on the `RAW` files, leaving the `JPEG` images untouched.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "add to library"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The \"add to library\" button allows you to add one or more existing images to the darktable library from the local filesystem. This process does not copy or move images but merely adds their details to the library database and creates XMP sidecar files for them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select only new pictures\n"
": Tick this box to restrict the _initial_ selection (when the dialog is loaded) to only those images that have not already been loaded into the darktable library. If you attempt to reload existing images into the darktable library, data for those images will be reloaded from the XMP sidecar files. A button is also available at the bottom of the dialog to select only \"new\" images for the currently-selected folder.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** \"Add to library\" does not create duplicates of your image files in a separate folder structure but processes them in-situ. The \"add to library\" process simply adds details of those images to darktable's library database (and creates an XMP sidecar file if applicable) allowing the images to be viewed and developed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This means that if you delete images from disk after having added them, darktable cannot access them any more. Moreover, darktable does not watch for changes in the filesystem. Any new images will not be shown until they are explicitly imported.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "copy & import"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This option copies images from another location on your filesystem (including mounted storage devices) and then adds the copied images to the darktable library. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following additional options are available to control the file and directory naming of the copied files. By default, only the \"import job\" option is shown -- click on the \"naming rules\" label or the expander icon beside it to show additional options:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"import job\n"
": The name of the import job (populated into the `$(JOBCODE)` variable).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"override todays's date\n"
": Enter a valid date/time (in `YYYY-MM-DD[Thh:mm:ss]` format) if you want to override the current date/time used when expanding the variables `$(YEAR)`, `$(MONTH)`, `$(DAY)`, `$(HOUR)`, `$(MINUTE)` and `$(SECONDS)`. Leave the field empty otherwise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"base directory naming pattern\n"
": The base directory part of the naming pattern (default `$(PICTURES_FOLDER)/Darktable`). Click on the icon beside the input field to choose a directory manually.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#: content/preferences-settings/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sub directory naming pattern\n"
": The sub directory part of the naming pattern (default `$(YEAR)$(MONTH)$(DAY)_$(JOBCODE)`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"keep original filename\n"
": Check this box to keep original the filename instead of using the pattern below when importing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"file naming pattern\n"
": The file name part of the naming pattern (default `$(YEAR)$(MONTH)$(DAY)_$(SEQUENCE).$(FILE_EXTENSION)`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"keep this window open\n"
": Keep the window open after the import is complete, allowing multiple imports but with different naming options.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Most of these options can also be set in [preferences > import](../../../../preferences-settings/import.md). See this section for more information about the available variables.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "copy & import from camera"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/import.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This option copies files from a connected camera to the local filesystem and then adds the copied images to the darktable library. It provides the same naming options as the \"copy & import\" dialog but does not allow places or folders to be selected. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/select.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "select"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/select.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Select images in the lighttable according to simple criteria.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/select.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select all\n"
": Select all images in the current collection.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/select.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select none\n"
": De-select all images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/select.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"invert selection\n"
": Select all images in the current collection that are not currently selected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/select.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select film roll\n"
": Select all images in the current collection that are in the same film roll as the currently-selected images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/select.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select untouched\n"
": Select all images in the current collection that have not yet been developed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "map"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "map settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Select preferred map data from various providers. Some will provide additional layers (satellite view etc.) which you can toggle.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"map source\n"
": Choose the provider to source map information from.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"max polygon points\n"
": The [find location](./find-location.md) module doesn't display polygons with more points than this for performance reasons. Usually a country polygon has between 50,000 and 150,000 points.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show OSD\n"
": Choose whether to display the OSD controls at the top-left of the center view.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"filtered images\n"
": Check this box to display only the images from the current collection (those shown in the filmstrip) in the center view. Un-check the box to display all images in the current library, where those images have associated GPS data. You can also toggle this option by pressing Ctrl+S.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"max images\n"
": The maximum number of thumbnails to display on the map.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"group size factor\n"
": Increase or decrease the size of area that causes images to be grouped.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"min images per group\n"
": The minimum number of images that need to be placed in the same position in order to automatically create an image group for them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/map-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"thumbnail display\n"
": Define what information to show on the map display\n"
": - _thumbnails_: Display image thumbnails along with a counter.\n"
": - _count_: Just display the number of images (to free space on the map). Hover over the number of images to show the corresponding thumbnail(s). A count-only marker behaves the same way as a normal image thumbnail, in terms of color coding, scrolling, drag and drop etc.\n"
": - _none_: Show nothing.\n"
": You can also cycle through these options by pressing Shift+S.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "locations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Create areas or locations and organize them as hierarchical tags. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A location is shown as a shape on the map when selected. Initially each location is represented as a square or circle and can be changed to a rectangle or ellipse by adjusting the shape's width and/or height.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A location can also be created from an OpenStreetMap region (city/country) polygon. To achieve this, first make sure the _max polygon points_ parameter is large enough (some country polygons use more than 150,000 points). Then select the desired location in the [find location](./find-location.md) module. When the corresponding region shape is displayed, a polygon symbol becomes available in the \"shape\" control (see below). Select it to create the new location.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Each location is stored as tag entry under the geotagging collection in the [collections](../shared/collections.md) module. The pipe “|” character can be used to insert a new level (a group of locations).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shape\n"
": Select the circle or rectangle symbol to choose the default shape for new locations. A polygon symbol is available when a shape is displayed by the [find location](./find-location.md) module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"new location / new sub-location\n"
": When no location is selected you can use the _new location_ button to create a location at root level. When a location is selected use the _new sub-location_ button to create a sub-location within the selected location.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"show all\n"
": Show or hide all locations that lie within the visible area of the current map.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "actions on the locations list"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"click\n"
": Select or de-select a location. If the location is not currently visible on the map, the map is automatically centered on that location.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Ctrl+click\n"
": Edit the name of the location. Press Enter to save changes or Esc to close the editing window without saving.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"right-click\n"
": Open a sub-menu which allows you to:\n"
": - Edit the name of the location.\n"
": - Delete the location.\n"
": - Update the filmstrip -- the filmstrip will be populated with all images in the selected location.\n"
": - Switch to the lighttable view and show a collection that contains all images in the selected location.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "actions on locations in the map"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_Note: The following actions have no effect on polygon locations._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"click and drag\n"
": Move the location shape to a new position on the map.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Ctrl+click or Ctrl+Shift+click\n"
": Move an image or a group of images and place them inside a location shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mouse scroll\n"
": When inside a location shape (but not over an image), increase or decrease the size of that shape.\n"
": When hovering over an image, cycle through the thumbnails of images located at that position on the map.\n"
": When outside a location shape (and not over an image) zoom the map in or out.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Shift+scroll\n"
": Increase or decrease the width of the location shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Ctrl+scroll\n"
": Increase or decrease the height of the location shape.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/locations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"click on a location shape\n"
": Select a different location when the _show all_ checkbox is selected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/find-location.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "find location"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/find-location.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Search for a location on the map. You must be connected to the internet to use this feature.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/find-location.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To use this module, type in a place name or address, press Enter and a list of results will be shown. Click on an item in the list and the map will zoom to that location. An outline covering that location or a pin pointing at the location will be displayed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/map/find-location.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "An outline (polygon) can be used to create a user location. Check the _max polygon points_ parameter in the [map settings](./map-settings.md) module to ensure that sufficient points are available for a polygon to be displayed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "print"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "print settings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Manage settings for the [print view](../../../print/_index.md) and initiate printing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "printer"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"printer\n"
": Select one of the installed printers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"media\n"
": The type of media loaded on the printer (Plain Paper, Luster Photo Paper, etc.).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"profile\n"
": The printer's ICC profile for the loaded paper. This is the profile specific to the printer and paper. This profile is the last color space transformation applied to the picture whose goal is to create a high quality print.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"intent\n"
": The print rendering intent (“perceptual”, “relative colorimetric”, “saturation” or “absolute colorimetric”). See [rendering intent](../../../special-topics/color-management/rendering-intent.md) for more details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"black point compensation\n"
": Whether to adjust the black point of the output profile, which is often lighter than the input profile. This should be “on” when the _intent_ is set to “relative colorimetric”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "page"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"paper size\n"
": The size of the paper on which to print.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"orientation\n"
": Portrait or landscape (note that darktable chooses the best fit by default).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"units\n"
": The unit to use for setting the margins: “mm”, “cm”, or “inch”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"margins\n"
": Set each margin separately, or all together by clicking on the middle “lock” button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"display grid\n"
": Select the grid size using the entry field (expressed in the currently selected unit). Tick the option to display the grid on the canvas.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"snap to grid\n"
": Help setting the image areas by snapping them to the grid for proper alignment.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"borderless mode required\n"
": Indicates whether the printer borderless mode is to be activated. This item is activated when the user's margins are smaller than the printer hardware margins. Note that it is only an indicator as it does not activate the borderless mode automatically.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "image layout"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"image width/height\n"
": This information field displays the actual image width and height (given with the selected units) on the paper.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scale factor\n"
": This information field displays the scaling of the image to fit on the paper. If this value is less than 1 the image is down-scaled, otherwise it is up-scaled. This is an important factor to watch -- a value that is too large (up-scale) may result in a low quality print. The corresponding dpi (dots per inch) is also displayed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"alignment\n"
": Select the alignment of the image on its area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"new image area button\n"
": Create a new image area. Drag and drop on the canvas to place it. If the option snap to grid is activated the area can be easily aligned to the grid lines. An image can be placed into this area by dragging it from the filmstrip and dropping it on the new area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"delete image area button\n"
": Remove the currently selected image area from the composition.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clear layout button\n"
": Remove all the image areas leaving the canvas empty.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following four fields represent the position of currently selected area on the page -- the top/left corner on the first line and the width/height of the area on the second line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When hovering an image area its position and size are displayed. It is also possible to grab the side and corner of the area to change the size or to drag the whole area to change its position.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The page layout can be recorded using a preset.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"profile\n"
": The export profile to use. This profile is the entry point used for the next transformation using the printer's ICC profile. Usually it is better to prefer a large gamut (e.g. Adobe RGB) rather than a smaller one (e.g. sRGB).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"intent\n"
": The rendering intent to use when exporting the image. For more information see [rendering intent](../../../special-topics/color-management/rendering-intent.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"style\n"
": Choose a style to apply when exporting the image -- defaults to “none”. See the [export](../shared/export.md) module for a more detailed discussion of applying a style during export.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": Whether the chosen style should be appended to the existing history stack or replace it completely. See the [export](../shared/export.md) module for more details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "print button"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/print/print-settings.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When clicked, the images are first exported using the selected options, then composed on the page and finally sent to the printer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "shared"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "focus peaking"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Identify which parts of the image contain sharp edges, which usually indicates that those areas are in focus.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Activate the module by clicking on the ![focus-peaking-icon](./focus-peaking/focus-peaking-icon.png#icon) icon. The sharp parts of the image will be highlighted with a yellow, green and blue overlay:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Focus peaking works by filtering out image noise, measuring the intensity gradients in the image and calculating average and standard deviation statistics. When the gradient of an edge differs significantly from the mean, the associated pixels are marked with a \"heat map\" indicating how sharp the edge is.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_yellow_ represents a large (6σ) jump in gradient, indicating a very sharp edge.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_green_ represents a medium (4σ) jump in gradient, indicating a reasonably sharp edge.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_blue_ represents a small (2σ) jump in gradient, indicating a slightly sharp edge.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![focus-peaking-overview](./focus-peaking/focus-peaking-overview.png#w75)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
